(4, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What role do smart contracts play in Web3?', 'They run automatically when conditions are met', 'They are written legal documents', 'They store passwords securely', 'They manage user logins'),
(5, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of these is an example of a Web3 application?', 'Uniswap', 'Facebook', 'Google Docs', 'PayPal'),
(6, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Why is Web3 seen as important for global users?', 'It enables financial access and services across borders', 'It reduces the need for mobile devices', 'It eliminates the use of the internet', 'It centralizes government policies globally'),
(8, 2, '\n  <h1>What is Blockchain Technology?</h1>\n<br>\n  <p><strong>Blockchain technology</strong> is one of the most revolutionary innovations of the 21st century, powering digital currencies like Bitcoin and transforming industries with its promise of transparency, security, and decentralization; But what exactly is blockchain?</p>\n\n  <p>At its core, a <strong>blockchain</strong> is a digital ledger like a database, that stores information in a secure and tamper-proof way. Unlike traditional databases controlled by a single entity (like a bank or company), blockchain is <em>decentralized</em>, meaning it is shared across many computers or nodes.</p>\n\n  <p>Each entry in this ledger is called a <strong>block</strong>, and these blocks are linked or \"chained\" together in chronological order—hence the name <strong>blockchain</strong>.</p>\n\n<br>\n\n  <h2>How Blockchain Works</h2>\n\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Transaction Occurs:</strong> A user initiates a transaction, such as sending cryptocurrency or recording data.</li>\n    <li><strong>Transaction is Verified:</strong> A network of computers (called nodes) validates the transaction using algorithms.</li>\n    <li><strong>Transaction is Added to a Block:</strong> Once verified, the transaction is grouped with others into a block.</li>\n    <li><strong>Block is Added to the Chain:</strong> The block is attached to the existing blockchain in a permanent, unchangeable way.</li>\n  </ol>\n\n  <p>Once a block is added, the data it contains is nearly impossible to alter without changing every subsequent block—a feature that makes blockchain highly secure.</p>\n\n\n  <br>\n    \n<div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> Analogy: How Blockchain Works</b> </h2>\n    <br>\n\n  <p>Imagine a classroom where every student has a notebook. This notebook is used to record every time someone borrows or returns a book from the class library.</p>\n\n  <h3>📘 Step-by-Step Analogy:</h3>\n\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>A Transaction Happens:</strong> John borrows a book titled \"Science Today\".</li>\n    <li><strong>Everyone Sees It:</strong> Instead of one person writing it down, all students copy the same transaction into their notebooks: <br>\n      <em>\"John borrowed \'Science Today\' at 10:00 AM\"</em>\n    </li>\n    <li><strong>Information is Locked In:</strong> Once all students write it down, that page in the notebook is considered complete and can\'t be changed.</li>\n    <li><strong>The Chain Continues:</strong> The next transaction (e.g., Mary returns \"Math Basics\") is recorded on a new page, following the previous one.</li>\n  </ol>\n\n  <p>This way, the class keeps a tamper-proof, shared history of every library transaction. If someone tries to cheat and change their notebook, it won’t match others—and everyone will know!</p>\n\n  <h3>🔒 How This Relates to Blockchain:</h3>\n\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>The notebook</strong> represents the blockchain.</li>\n    <li><strong>The students</strong> are like the network nodes (computers).</li>\n    <li><strong>The recorded entries</strong> are the blocks.</li>\n    <li><strong>The linking of pages</strong> is the chain of blocks.</li>\n    <li><strong>Consensus among students</strong> ensures no one can fake or alter history.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <p><strong>In summary:</strong> Just like the classroom notebook system, blockchain creates a shared, secure, and permanent record of transactions—open to all, but impossible to alter without agreement from everyone involved.</p>\n\n</div>\n\n\n\n<br>\n  <h2>Key Features of Blockchain</h2>\n\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Decentralization:</strong> No single authority controls the blockchain. All participants have access to the same information.</li>\n    <li><strong>Transparency:</strong> Transactions are visible to all participants in the network.</li>\n    <li><strong>Security:</strong> Blockchain uses cryptographic algorithms to ensure data is secure and cannot be tampered with.</li>\n    <li><strong>Immutability:</strong> Once data is added to the blockchain, it cannot be changed or deleted.</li>\n    <li><strong>Consensus Mechanism:</strong> Decisions are made collectively by the network, usually through methods like Proof of Work (PoW) or Proof of Stake (PoS).</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h2>Applications of Blockchain</h2>\n\n  <p>Blockchain is not limited to cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin or Ethereum. It has a wide range of applications across various sectors:</p>\n\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Finance:</strong> Enabling peer-to-peer payments, eliminating the need for middlemen, and increasing transaction speed.</li>\n    <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Storing patient records securely and giving patients control over their data.</li>\n    <li><strong>Supply Chain:</strong> Tracking products from source to destination, ensuring authenticity and quality.</li>\n    <li><strong>Voting Systems:</strong> Creating tamper-proof digital voting systems to improve transparency and trust.</li>\n    <li><strong>Real Estate:</strong> Recording property ownership and transaction history in a secure manner.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h2>Advantages of Blockchain</h2>\n\n  <ul>\n    <li>Reduces fraud and corruption</li>\n    <li>Improves efficiency and speed of transactions</li>\n    <li>Lowers operational costs by eliminating intermediaries</li>\n    <li>Empowers users with control over their own data</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h2>Challenges of Blockchain</h2>\n\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Scalability:</strong> Some blockchains are slow and cannot handle a large number of transactions.</li>\n    <li><strong>Energy Consumption:</strong> Proof of Work systems can use massive amounts of electricity.</li>\n    <li><strong>Regulatory Uncertainty:</strong> Many governments are still deciding how to regulate blockchain technology.</li>\n    <li><strong>Complexity:</strong> The technology is still new and difficult for many to understand or implement.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n  <h2>Conclusion</h2>\n\n  <p>Blockchain technology has the potential to transform industries by making systems more secure, transparent, and decentralized. While it comes with its own set of challenges, its advantages are far-reaching. As innovation continues, blockchain is likely to become an even more significant part of our digital future.</p>\n\n  <p><em>Understanding blockchain today means being ready for tomorrow’s world of technology and finance.</em></p>\n\n', 'Intro to Blockchain Technology', '1', 'What is a blockchain at its core?', 'A digital ledger that stores data securely and chronologically', 'A type of cryptocurrency', 'A central database controlled by governments', 'An online payment processor'),
(9, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'In blockchain, what is a block?', 'A group of verified transactions linked in the ledger', 'A cryptocurrency wallet', 'A password-protected folder', 'A central authority'),
(10, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which feature of blockchain ensures that once data is recorded, it cannot be altered?', 'Immutability', 'Transparency', 'Decentralization', 'Encryption'),
(11, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is the purpose of consensus mechanisms in blockchain?', 'To ensure agreement among nodes before adding a block', 'To connect users to social media', 'To encrypt messages before sending them', 'To monitor user activity'),
(12, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of the following is a real-life analogy used to describe how blockchain works?', 'A classroom notebook shared by all students', 'A diary locked in a safe', 'An online spreadsheet only one person can edit', 'A chalkboard used by the teacher'),
(13, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of the following is NOT a challenge of blockchain?', 'Centralized control of data', 'Scalability', 'Regulatory uncertainty', 'High energy consumption'),
(14, 3, '\n  <p>In the digital age, the concepts of <strong>cryptography</strong> and <strong>cryptocurrency</strong> are \n    becoming increasingly important, especially as the world moves toward decentralized systems, blockchain-based \n    platforms, and digital finance. While they are often mentioned together, they are not the same thing; However, they \n    are <em>deeply connected</em>.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2>What is Cryptography?</h2>\n  <p><strong>Cryptography</strong> is the science of protecting data through mathematical techniques. \n    It\'s goal is to secure communication and ensure that only intended recipients can understand the message or access the data.</p>\n  <br>\n\n  <h3> <u class=\"b-6\"> <b>Core Functions of Cryptography</b> </u></h3>\n  Cryptography serves four main functions that are crucial for secure communication and data integrity, these are:\n  <br>\n  <br>\n\n <ol class=\"list-decimal ml-6\">\n    <li><strong>Confidentiality : </strong>  Prevents unauthorized access to information.</li>\n    <li><strong>Integrity : </strong>  Ensures the information hasn’t been altered.</li>\n    <li><strong>Authentication : </strong>  Verifies the identity of users or sources.</li>\n    <li><strong>Non-repudiation : </strong>  Prevents denial of involvement in a transaction.</li>\n  </ol>\n\n    <br>\n  <h2><u><b>Types of Cryptography</b></u></h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Symmetric Encryption</strong>: The same key is used to encrypt and decrypt data.</li>\n    <li><strong>Asymmetric Encryption</strong>: Uses a public and private key pair.</li>\n  </ol>\n<br>\n  <p>\n    <strong>Symmetric encryption</strong> is faster and suitable for large data, while <strong>asymmetric encryption</strong> is more secure and used for key exchange and digital signatures.\n     It is important to note that both types of cryptography are essential for the functioning of cryptocurrencies, as they provide the necessary security and trust mechanisms.\n    <br>\n  </p>\n  <br>\n\n    <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> NOTEWORTHY</b> </h2>\n    <br>\n        It is necessary to mention cryptography in the build up of Web3 studies; However, deeper knowledge of cryptography must be \n        sourced through dedicated texts and academic research works which are far beyond the scope of this lesson.\n    </div>\n\n\n  <br><br>\n  <h2> <u><b> What is Cryptocurrency? </b></u></h2>\n  <p><strong>Cryptocurrency</strong> is a type of digital or virtual currency that uses <strong>cryptography</strong> to secure transactions, control the creation of new units, and validate asset transfers.</p>\n<br><br>\n\n  <h2><u> <b> Relationship between Cryptography and Cryptocurrency  </b> </u></h2>\n  <p>Cryptography is <strong> what makes cryptocurrency possible</strong>. Without cryptography, cryptocurrencies would be easy to \n    counterfeit, vulnerable to fraud, and impossible to verify.\n    Therefore, cryptography provides the foundation for the security, integrity, and trustworthiness of cryptocurrencies.</p>  \nCryptography makes cryptocurrencies possible by the implementation of several key concepts and technologies. Here’s how they work together and the benefits of cryptography:\n<br>\n  <h2><b> 1. Digital Signatures</b></h2>\n  <p>When someone sends cryptocurrency, they must prove ownership of the funds using a <strong>private key</strong>.</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>A <strong>digital signature</strong> is created using cryptographic algorithms.</li>\n    <li>It is verified by others using the sender’s <strong>public key</strong>.</li>\n   This ensures authenticity without revealing the private key, It\'s like signing a check, but mathematically, and in a way that can’t be forged.\n  </ul>\n  <br>\n\n\n\n  <h2> <b> 2. Hash Functions</b></h2>\n  <p>A hash function turns input into a fixed-length string. It is one-way and impossible to reverse.</p>\n  <p>Even small changes in input create vastly different outputs.</p>\n  <h3> Use Cases :</h3>\n  <ol>\n    <li>Transaction IDs</li>\n    <li>Block verification</li>\n    <li>Proof-of-Work (e.g., mining)</li>\n     This special functions are only possible through cryptography.\n  </ol>\n   \n\n\n\n  <br>\n  <h2> <b>3. Wallets and Key Pairs </b> </h2>\n  <p>A crypto wallet stores your keys, not your money.</p>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Public Key</strong>: Like a bank account number</li>\n    <li><strong>Private Key</strong>: Like your ATM PIN</li>\n\n    This special keys  are generated using cryptographic algorithms, ensuring that only the owner can access their funds.\n  </ol>\n\n\n  <br>\n  <h2><b> 4. Secure Transactions on the Blockchain</b></h2>\n  <p>Each crypto transaction is encrypted, signed, and verified using cryptographic functions. No banks are needed; the network itself is the trust layer.</p>\n  <br>\n\n\n\n  <h2> <b> 5. Consensus Mechanisms Use Cryptography</b> </h2>\n  <p>Cryptocurrencies use consensus to agree on transactions:</p>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Proof of Work (PoW)</strong> – Mining with computational puzzles</li>\n    <li><strong>Proof of Stake (PoS)</strong> – Validators hold coins to propose blocks</li>\n  </ol>\n<br>\n\n\n\n  <h2> <b> <u>  Examples of cryptocurrencies, and cryptographic applications </u></b></h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Bitcoin & Ethereum</strong> – Core cryptographic networks</li>\n    <li><strong>NFTs</strong> – Verified with cryptographic proofs</li>\n    <li><strong>zk-SNARKs</strong> – Enables private transactions</li>\n    <li><strong>Signal & Secure Messaging</strong> – Uses cryptographic protocols</li>\n  </ol>\n\n\n  <br>\n  <h2> <b> <u>Challenges of Cryptocurrency </u></b> </h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Key Loss :  &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>  Lose your key, lose access</li>\n    <li><strong>User Error : &nbsp;</strong> – No support to recover lost funds</li>\n    <li><strong>Scalability :  &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong> – Some blockchains are slow and requires enormous resources to scale</li>\n    <li><strong>Quantum Threat :  &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong> – May break current encryption</li>\n  </ol>\n\n  <br>\n\n  <h2> <u> <b>  Summary </b></u></h2>\n  <p>Cryptography and cryptocurrency are inseparable. One is the <strong>science of security</strong>, and the other is the <strong>application of that science to money</strong>. Together, they enable a new era of digital finance where individuals control their assets.</p>\n', 'Cryptography and Cryptocurrency', NULL, 'What is the primary purpose of cryptography in cryptocurrency systems?', 'To secure and validate transactions', 'To generate profits', 'To reduce internet speed', 'To control user data'),
(15, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which cryptographic technique is used to ensure a transaction was signed by the rightful owner?', 'Digital signature', 'Public blockchain', 'Mining', 'Proof of stake'),
(16, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of the following is a characteristic of a hash function in blockchain?', 'It produces a fixed-length output', 'It can be easily reversed', 'It compresses files', 'It generates a wallet address directly'),
(17, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'In public-key cryptography, which key is shared openly?', 'Public key', 'Private key', 'Symmetric key', 'Hash key'),
(18, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which type of encryption uses two different keys: one public and one private?', 'Asymmetric encryption', 'Symmetric encryption', 'Quantum encryption', 'Static encryption'),
(19, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Why is cryptography essential to cryptocurrency?', 'It allows secure, trustless transactions', 'It helps in government regulation', 'It provides customer support', 'It creates smart contracts automatically'),
(26, 4, '\n  <p>Unlike traditional currencies issued by governments, cryptocurrencies are:\n    <ol  class=\"list-decimal list-inside\">\n      <li>Decentralized</li>\n      <li>Borderless</li>\n      <li>Digital-only</li>\n      <li>Stored on a blockchain</li>\n    </ol>\n  </p>\n  <br>\n\n <h2> <u><b>Why Is Crypto even accepted as money?</b> </u> </h2> \n    \n  <p>Ultimately, <strong>money is a shared belief</strong>; If a high number of people believes that a particular material that has certain properties is a medium of exchange, then that material becomes \"Money\".</p>\n  However, there are basic properties of Money, Cryptocurrency (like Bitcoin or Ethereum) is accepted as money because it has these properties, though digital and decentralized. \n  To be accepted as money, an item must have these properties or functions :\n<br><br>\n\n<table>\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>1. Medium of exchange</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\"> People must be able to use it to buy goods and services.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>2. Store of Value </b>  </td>\n    <td>It must keep its value over time so people can save it.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>3. Unit of Account</b>  </td>\n    <td>Prices must be able to be expressed in it .</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>4. Divisibility</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">It must be easily divided into smaller parts.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>5. Portability</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">It must be easy to carry and transfer .</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>6. Durability</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">It must withstand wear and tear.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>7. Fungibility</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">Each unit must be interchangeable (just as a one dollar bill is the same as another).</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>10. Acceptability</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">People must generally agree to accept it as payment.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>11. Limited Supply</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">There should be a controlled supply to prevent inflation .</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>12. Security</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">It must be secure against counterfeiting.</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td> <b>13. Accessibility</b>  </td>\n    <td class=\"indent-2\">It should be easy for people to access and use .</td>\n  </tr>\n\n</table>\n\n<br>\n\n  <p>These functions are why we accept things like gold, silver, or even paper money as \"money\", because they allow us to trade, save, and measure value. Cryptocurrency meets these functions in many ways, and is largely accepted because:</p>\n<br>\n  <ol class=\"space-y-4 list-decimal list-inside\"> \n\n      <li>\n      <strong> People trust it\'s Technology :</strong>\n\n      Crypto is secured by blockchain technology and cryptography; This makes it tamper-proof, transparent, and decentralized.\n   The world accepts it because the rules are clear, secure, and enforced by code, not banks or governments.\n</li>\n\n  <li>\n\n      <strong> It is borderless and fast :</strong>\n\n      With Crypto,\n\n      <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside  indent-4\">\n        <li>People can send money to anyone, anywhere in the world.</li>\n        <li>Transactions are fast and often cost less than traditional methods.</li>\n        <li>You don’t need a bank or even government permission.</li>\n      </ol>\n      <br>\n      This makes it very useful for international trade, remittances, and online payments, and is especially useful in countries with unstable currencies and/or limited banking access.\n\n  </li>\n\n\n  <li>     \n       <strong>Limited Supply : </strong>\n      Bitcoin for example, has a maximum supply of 21 million coins; Scarcity makes it similar to gold, which people trust to hold value over time.\n  </li>\n\n\n  <li>\n      <strong>People Control Their Money : </strong>\n\n      Cryptocurrency gives users ownership and control over their funds without needing banks or governments. This means:\n        \n      <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside  indent-4\">\n\n\n      <li>No one can freeze your account.</li>\n\n      <li>No one can stop your transaction.</li>\n      <li>No inflation from central banks printing more.</li>\n      </ol>\n      <br>\n      This financial freedom is very appealing to many people, especially in places with corrupt or unstable governments.\n</li>\n\n</ol>\n<br>\n\n  <h3> <u><b> How did people come to believe that Cryptocurrency Is money? </b></u>   </h3>\n  <br>\n\n  <p>People came to believe that <strong>cryptocurrency is money</strong> over time due to a combination of economic behavior, utility, technological expansion,  and social consensus; \n    Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies began fulfilling the roles traditional money played because people used them to buy goods, saved them as investments, and even priced items. \n    people trusted cryptocurrencies because they are built on <strong>blockchain technology</strong>, which is secure, transparent, and decentralized. This means that their investments were safe and hassle free. In regions with unstable banks or hyperinflation, crypto became a safe alternative.</p>\n  As more people and institutions began to buy, use, and accept crypto, a belief formed: <em> \"If others treat it like money, maybe I should too.\" </em> This social proof helped drive adoption, and now for many, crypto is not just digital money, it is now a strong movement and a generally important aspect of finance and technology.</p>\n\n  <br>\n  \n\n  <h3> <u> <b>Some popular Cryptocurrencies include: </b></u>   </h3>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Bitcoin (BTC)</li>\n    <li>Ethereum (ETH)</li>\n    <li>Litecoin (LTC)</li>\n    <li>Solana (SOL)</li>\n  </ul>\n', 'Cryptocurrency as Money', NULL, 'What key property allows cryptocurrency to be transferred across countries without restriction?', 'Borderless', 'Durability', 'Divisibility', 'Fungibility'),
(27, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Why is cryptocurrency often seen as a secure way to store and send money?', 'Because it is built on blockchain and cryptography', 'Because it is printed by central banks', 'Because it is backed by gold', 'Because it is taxed by governments'),
(28, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of these is NOT a function of money that cryptocurrency must fulfill?', 'Colorfulness', 'Portability', 'Divisibility', 'Durability'),
(29, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Why does limited supply make Bitcoin valuable?', 'Because scarcity creates value, like gold', 'Because it is created by banks', 'Because it has no fees', 'Because it is easy to print'),
(30, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of the following is a reason people began to believe crypto is money?', 'It fulfills roles like buying, saving, and pricing goods', 'It looks like cash', 'It is issued by government', 'It can’t be used for savings'),
(31, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of the following is a popular cryptocurrency?', 'Solana (SOL)', 'MetaPay', 'PayPal Token', 'DigiNaira'),
(32, 5, '\n  <p>Cryptocurrency can seem like a foreign language when you\'re just starting out. From blockchains and wallets to gas fees and HODL, the crypto world is full of unique terms of which understanding them  is essential for anyone looking to get involved with cryptocurrency, whether as a user, investor, developer, or enthusiast.</p>\n\n  <p>Let\'s look at some of the most common and important terminologies in cryptocurrency,all explained in simple terms.</p>\n\n  <h2> <b> 1. Blockchain/Network </b> </h2>\n  <p>A blockchain is a digital ledger that records all transactions across a network of computers. Each group of transactions forms a \"block,\" and these blocks are linked together in a chain. It is the foundational technology behind cryptocurrencies, every blockchain has it\'s coin.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2> <b> 2. Coin or Token </b> </h2>\n  <p>A Coin or Token is any digital form of money that is decentralized and built on blockchain technology. Examples include Bitcoin, Ethereum, and Solana. Coins are made specifically for the blockchain, while Tokens are crypto built on an already existing blockchain. </p>\n  <p><strong>Note:</strong>Though they are not the same, Token/Coin are used interchangeably to mean the same thing in practise.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2> <b>3. Wallet</b></h2>\n  <p>A wallet is a software or hardware tool used to store, send, and receive cryptocurrencies, it is similar to a bank account. It contains your public and private keys, and your wallet address all generated from your seed phrase.</p>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Hot Wallet:</strong> Connected to the internet, e.g. Metamask, Trustwallet, Phantom e.t.c.</li>\n    <li><strong>Cold Wallet:</strong> Offline, more secure e.g., hardware wallets like Ledger, they are usually specialized devices for crypto transactions.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br>\n\n  \n  <h2><b>4. Seed phrase / Recovery Phrase</b></h2>\n  <p>This is the 12 or 24 words phrase that gives access to a wallets private key, everybody that has this words in the right order will access the funds in the wallet, so it is meant to be protected and must not be revealed to 2nd party;\n     it is recommended that they are handwritten on paper and filed up safely, losing them also means losing access to your account. </p>\n<br>\n\n  \n  <h2><b>5. Private Key / Public Key</b></h2>\n  <p>Private and public keys are unique cryptographic keys used in blockchain transactions, they are generated from seed phrases and are uniquely bound to a particular seed phrase. They are essential for securing your wallet and authorizing transactions.</p>\n  <p>Never share your private key with anyone, as it gives full control over your wallet and funds. If someone has your private key, they can access and transfer your cryptocurrency without your permission.</p>\n  <p>Simply put : </p>\n  <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside  indent-4\">\n    <li><strong>Public Key: </strong> Shared openly, and can be used at the backend of dapps to generate your wallet address.</li>\n    <li><strong>Private Key: </strong> Kept secret and used to authorize transactions. Losing or exposing this means losing the sole access and ownership to your funds.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <strong>Note : </strong>A public key is not a wallet address, it is a longer string of characters that is used to generate the wallet address; do not transfer funds to a public key.</p>\n  <br>\n\n  <h2><b> 6. Wallet Address </b></h2>\n    <p>A crypto address is a unique string of characters used to send or receive cryptocurrency, similar to a bank account number.</p>\n      <p>It is derived from your public key and can be shared with others to receive funds; Always double-check the address before sending crypto, as transactions are irreversible, to prevent mistakes, always copy and paste addresses, do not type them.</p>\n  <p><strong> Example : </strong> A Bitcoin address looks like this: <code> <b>1A1zP1eP5QGefi2DMPTfTL5SLmv7DivfNa</b></code></p>\n  <p><strong>Note : </strong> Always ensure you are using the correct address format for the specific cryptocurrency you are dealing with, as different coins have different address formats; you will develop this knowledge with time.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2><b>7. Gas Fee </b></h2>\n  <p>A gas fee is a small payment required to perform a transaction or execute a smart contract on a blockchain. It pays the network validators for processing.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2> <b>8. Gas Limit </b></h2>\n  <p>The gas limit is the maximum amount of gas you are willing to spend on a transaction. If the transaction requires more gas than the limit, it will fail.</p>\n<br>\n\n <h2><strong>9. DApp (Decentralized Application)</strong></h2>\n  <p>A DApp is an application that runs on a decentralized network, typically using smart contracts. DApps are open-source, operate autonomously, and are not controlled by a single entity.</p>  \n  <br>\n\n  <h2><b>10. Faucet</b></h2>\n  <p>A faucet is a website or app that gives out small amounts of cryptocurrency for free, usually to help users learn how to use wallets and transactions. It is often used to distribute testnet coins for developers and testers.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2> <b>11. Testnet </b></h2>\n  <p>A testnet is a separate blockchain used for testing purposes. It allows developers to experiment with new features without risking real money. Testnets use test coins that have no real value.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2><b>12. Exchange </b></h2>\n  <p>A cryptocurrency exchange is a platform where you can buy, sell, or trade cryptocurrencies. They are grouped into :</p>\n   <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside  indent-4\">\n    <li><strong>Centralized Exchange (CEX):</strong> Operated by a company, requires registration, and holds user funds; e.g Binance, Coinbase, Gate.io,MEXC, e.t.c</li>\n    <li><strong>Decentralized Exchange (DEX):</strong> Peer-to-peer trading without intermediaries, users retain control of their funds; e.g Jupiter, Uniswap, Pancakeswap, e.t.c </li> \n    <li><strong>Hybrid Exchange:</strong> Combines features of both CEX and DEX, offering a balance of security and usability; e.g. Kado, dYdX, e.t.c</li>\n  </ol>\n<br>\n\n <h2><b>13. Altcoin </b></h2>\n  <p>Any cryptocurrency other than Bitcoin is called an altcoin (alternative coin). Examples include Ethereum, Litecoin, and Solana.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2><b>14. Whitepaper </b></h2>\n  <p>A whitepaper is a document that explains the purpose, technology, and plans behind a cryptocurrency or blockchain project. Bitcoin’s whitepaper was published by Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008.</p>\n<br>\n\n   <h2><b>15. Token Symbol & Decimals </b></h2>\n  <p>\n        Every cryptocurrency has a ticker used to identify the token e.g, Bitcoin\'s ticker is BTC, Ethereum is ETH, and Solana is SOL.\n</p>\n<br>\n\n   <h2><b>16. Tokenomics</b></h2>\n    <p>Short for \"Token Economics\", refers to the economic model behind a token i.e how it is created, distributed, used, and maintained to give it value.</p>\n<br>\n\n\n\n <h2><strong>17. Total Supply</strong> </h2>\n <p>The Maximum number of a token that will ever created.</p>\n <br>\n\n\n <h2><strong>18. Circulating Supply </strong></h2>\n <p>The total number of Tokens currently in public circulation.</p>\n <br>\n\n <h2><strong>19. Initial Supply</strong></h2>\n <p>The Total number of the Tokens released at launch.</p>\n <br>\n\n  <h2><strong>20. Market Cap </strong></h2>\n  <p>Market capitalization is calculated as price of a coin multiplied by the total number of coins in circulation. It is used to measure the size and popularity of a cryptocurrency.</p>\n  <br>\n\n <h2><strong>21. Burning</strong></h2>\n <p>This is the act of permanently removing tokens to reduce supply, it is done by sending tokens to a non-existent or non-accessible address; burning creates scarcity, thereby increasing the value of a crypto token.</p>\n <br>\n\n  <h2><b>22. Emission Rate </b></h2>\n  <p>Emission rate is a term used to describe the rate at which new tokens are created and introduced into circulation,  It may be per block, per day, or per year; It is an important aspect of tokenomics, influencing supply and demand dynamics.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2><b>23. Mining </b></h2>\n  <p>Mining is the process of verifying transactions and adding them to the blockchain. It is mostly used in Proof of Work systems like Bitcoin. Miners are rewarded with new cryptocurrency for their work.</p>\n  <br>\n\n\n  <h2><b>24. Proof of Work (PoW) vs Proof of Stake (PoS)</b></h2>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Proof of Work (PoW):</strong> A consensus mechanism where miners solve complex mathematical problems to validate transactions and secure the network. It requires significant computational power and energy.</li>\n    <li><strong>Proof of Stake (PoS):</strong> A consensus mechanism where validators are chosen to create new blocks based on the number of coins they hold and are willing to \"stake\" as collateral. It is more energy-efficient than PoW.</li> \n<br>\n\n  <h2><b>25. Staking</b></h2>\n  <p>Staking involves locking up cryptocurrency in a wallet to support the operations of a blockchain network. It is used in Proof of Stake systems, and stakers are rewarded with additional coins.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2><b>26. Volatility</b></h2>\n  <p>Volatility refers to how much and how quickly the price of a cryptocurrency changes. Crypto is known for being highly volatile.</p>\n<br>\n  \n  <h2><b>27. FUD</b></h2>\n  <p>FUD stands for Fear, Uncertainty, and Doubt. It is a term used when negative news or rumors affect the price of a cryptocurrency, often causing panic selling.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2><b>28. HODL</b></h2>\n  <p>Originally a typo of \"hold\", HODL means \"Hold On for Dear Life\". It encourages crypto holders to keep their coins long-term despite market drops.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2><b>29. Pump and Dump</b></h2>\n  <p>A scheme where the price of a cryptocurrency is artificially inflated (pumped) and then quickly sold off (dumped) for profit. This often affects small or low-volume coins.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2><b>30. Bear Market / Bull Market </b></h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Bull Market:</strong> Prices are rising, and optimism is high.</li>\n    <li><strong>Bear Market:</strong> Prices are falling, and pessimism dominates.</li>\n  </ol>\n<br>\n\n  <h2><b>31. NFT (Non-Fungible Token)</b></h2>\n  <p>A type of digital asset that represents ownership of unique items like art, music, or game collectibles. NFTs are mostly built on Ethereum.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2><b>32. Airdrops</b></h2>\n  <p>An airdrop is a method of rewarding the holders or participants of a specific cryptocurrency with that crypto token.\n     It is often used to promote new projects or reward loyal users.</p>\n     <p>Airdrops are used to raise awareness about a new project or to incentivize users to engage with a platform.</p>\n  <p>To receive an airdrop, you usually need to hold a certain amount of a specific cryptocurrency in your wallet at a given time, or you may need to complete certain tasks like following social media accounts, joining a community, or helping in the development of the project.</p>\n  <p>Note: Always be cautious of airdrops, as some may be scams or require you to share sensitive information. Legitimate airdrops will never ask for your private key or seed phrase.</p>\n<br>\n\n  <h2> <strong>33. ICO / IDO</strong></h2>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>ICO:</strong> Initial Coin Offering — a fundraising method where a new cryptocurrency is sold to early investors.</li>\n    <li><strong>IDO:</strong> Initial DEX Offering — a similar process launched on decentralized exchanges.</li>\n  </ol>\n<br><br>\n  <p>Cryptocurrency is a fast-evolving space with its own language, these terminologies are more than buzzwords, they form the foundation of understanding how crypto works. \n    Whether you plan on trading, investing, building, or just learning, familiarizing yourself with these terms will help you navigate the crypto world with confidence.</p>\n', 'Beginner Terminologies in crypto', NULL, 'What is the primary function of a blockchain in cryptocurrency?', 'It records all transactions in a digital ledger across a network', 'It creates images for NFTs', 'It issues fiat money', 'It converts crypto to fiat'),
(33, 5, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is the main difference between a Coin and a Token in crypto?', 'Coins are native to their own blockchain; tokens are built on existing blockchains', 'Tokens are physical while coins are digital', 'Tokens are used only for gaming', 'Coins cannot be traded online'),
(34, 5, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is a seed phrase used for in cryptocurrency wallets?', 'To recover access to your crypto wallet', 'To boost mining rewards', 'To register on exchanges', 'To stake coins in PoS systems'),
(35, 5, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What does HODL mean in crypto slang?', 'Hold On for Dear Life', 'High Order Digital Ledger', 'Handle Only Decentralized Ledger', 'Hope Of Digital Liquidity'),
(36, 5, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of these is a characteristic of a cold wallet?', 'It is not connected to the internet and offers higher security', 'It allows quick trading on exchanges', 'It is built only for NFTs', 'It is automatically synced to a DEX'),
(37, 5, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is the purpose of gas fees on a blockchain network?', 'To pay validators for processing transactions', 'To fuel mining hardware', 'To increase market cap', 'To reduce staking rewards'),
(38, 6, '  <h2><b>1. Whitepaper</b></h2>\n  <p>\n    Bitcoin as the first cryptocurrency was introduced by Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008 through the whitepaper titled\n    <strong>\"Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System.\"</strong> It outlined a decentralized network that enables direct\n    financial transactions between parties without relying on trusted intermediaries. By solving the double-spending problem\n    through a consensus mechanism called <em>Proof-of-Work</em>, the whitepaper laid the foundation for a trustless digital\n    payment system. It introduced concepts like distributed ledgers (blockchains), mining, and incentivized validation that are now\n    standard across the cryptocurrency ecosystem.\n  </p>\n  <p class=\"text-red-200  indent-8\"> &#x27A1;<a href=\"https://bitcoin.org/bitcoin.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"text-red-200  indent-8\"> Read the Bitcoin whitepaper </a>  </p>\n<br><br>\n\n <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> DOUBLE-SPENDING PROBLEM</b> </h2>\n    <br>\n\n    Since the existence of digital technology, the double-spending problem was a fundamental issue hindering the creation of digital currencies: the risk that a digital token \n    or coin could be duplicated and spent more than once; unlike physical cash, which can only be handed over once\n     and cannot be used again by the sender, without a central authority, like a bank,\n     keeping track of balances and transactions, there\'s no built-in way to prevent someone from copying a \n     digital coin and sending it to multiple recipients if it was created.\n<br><br>\n\nImagine sending someone $10 as an image via WhatsApp. The recipient sees it, but you still have the same image and can send it again to someone else. This highlights the core issue, without a trusted third party or a reliable verification system, digital money is inherently insecure.\n<br><br>\n\nThe double-spending problem was one of the biggest barriers to the creation of a viable digital currency, and Bitcoin\'s breakthrough was to solve it without needing a central authority. This innovation is the foundation of all modern cryptocurrencies.\n\n </div>\n <br><br>\n\n\n  <h2><b>2. Tokenomics</b></h2>\n  <p>\n    Bitcoin\'s economic model is deflationary, designed to create scarcity and long-term value preservation. It operates on a fixed\n    set of rules embedded in its protocol. These rules determine how new coins are created, how transactions are validated, and how incentives are distributed to participants in the network. \n  </p>\n  <p>\n    The key components of Bitcoin\'s tokenomics include : \n  </p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Maximum Supply:</strong> BTC has a hard coded total supply of 21 million BTC.</li>\n    <li><strong>Block Time:</strong> This is the average amount of time it takes the network to validate and add a new block of transactions to the blockchain, which for BTC is approximately 10 minutes.</li>\n    <li><strong>Reward Halving:</strong>The amount of BTC given to miners in halved, this simply means that supply of new bitcoins into the market is halved, and for BTC, this happens at every 210,000 blocks (4 years); current reward is 3.125 BTC.</li>\n    <li><strong>Mining Incentives:</strong>Miners are rewarded through the combination of block rewards and transaction fees.</li>\n    <li><strong>Deflationary Nature:</strong> Reduced issuance over time; All BTC is expected to be mined by 2140</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <br><br>\n\n  <h2> <b>3. Adoption and Utility</b></h2>\n  <p>\n    Bitcoin’s adoption has grown from a niche internet experiment to a globally recognized financial asset. Its decentralized\n    architecture appeals to both individual users seeking privacy and institutions seeking portfolio diversification, while its\n    utility extends beyond mere speculation, encompassing various financial applications, these cases includes:\n  </p>\n  <br>\n\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Retail:</strong> It is adopted as a store of value, hedge against inflation, and means of digital payment.</li>\n    <li><strong>Institutional:</strong>It is held by companies like MicroStrategy, Tesla, and investment funds; now integrated into ETFs and futures</li>\n    <li><strong>Geopolitical:</strong> BTC is used by citizens in inflation-prone countries; recognized as legal tender in El Salvador</li>\n  </ol>\n  <ol>\n    <li><strong>Store of Value:</strong>BTC is often referred to as “digital gold” due to its scarcity and decentralized nature</li>\n    <li><strong>Medium of Exchange:</strong> Accepted by merchants and services; fast transactions enabled via the Lightning Network</li>\n    <li><strong>Remittance:</strong>Because it is digital, it enables low-cost, borderless money transfers without centralized institutions.</li>\n    <li><strong>Collateral:</strong>It is used in crypto lending platforms and decentralized finance (DeFi) products.</li>\n    <li><strong>Financial Sovereignty:</strong>Cryptocurrency like BTC enables users to retain full control over their funds without banks.</li>\n    <li><strong>Market Impact:</strong> Bitcoin price movements often dictates the overall crypto market trends.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br><br>\n\n   <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> THE FUTURE OF BTC </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n\n    Bitcoin(BTC) is the first and most well-known cryptocurrency, it set the standards in decentralized digital finance, remains the benchmark by which all other\n    cryptocurrencies are compared and continues to dominate the finance markets with an estimated increase in price of 100% for every halving cycle which happens every four years. Unlike Gold, BTC has a fixed supply of 21 million coins, making it a deflationary asset.\n    The dominance of Bitcoin in the cryptocurrency market is expected to continue, as it has the largest market cap and liquidity among all cryptocurrencies.\n   </div>\n\n', 'Bitcoin', NULL, 'What is the title of the original Bitcoin whitepaper by Satoshi Nakamoto?', 'Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System', 'Bitcoin: The Internet of Money', 'Bitcoin: A Trustless Digital Economy', 'Bitcoin and the Future of Money'),
(39, 6, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What fundamental problem did Bitcoin solve to enable digital currency?', 'The double-spending problem', 'The transaction fee dilemma', 'The volatility issue', 'The central bank reliance');
INSERT INTO `questions_and_answers` (`id`, `learning_cycle`, `material`, `material_title`, `lesson_video`, `question`, `answer`, `option_1`, `option_2`, `option_3`) VALUES
(40, 6, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is the maximum supply of Bitcoin that will ever exist?', '21 million BTC', '100 million BTC', '50 million BTC', 'Unlimited BTC'),
(41, 6, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'How often is Bitcoin block reward halved?', 'Every 210,000 blocks (approximately 4 years)', 'Every 1 million transactions', 'Annually on January 1st', 'Every 2 years'),
(42, 6, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of the following is NOT listed as a use case for Bitcoin?', 'Airline ticketing system', 'Store of value', 'Remittance', 'Collateral in DeFi'),
(43, 6, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which country has officially recognized Bitcoin as legal tender?', 'El Salvador', 'Canada', 'Germany', 'Singapore'),
(44, 7, '\n\n    <div class=\" mx-auto shadow-md rounded-lg \">\n\n        <h1 class=\"text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900\">Alternative Coins (Altcoins): A Comprehensive Overview</h1>\n\n        <section>\n            <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-semibold mb-2\">Introduction to Altcoins</h2>\n            <p>\n                \"Altcoin\" is a portmanteau of “alternative” and “coin.” It refers to all cryptocurrencies <strong>other than Bitcoin</strong>.\n                Since Bitcoin’s launch in 2009, thousands of other cryptocurrencies have been developed with varying use cases,\n                technologies, and communities. These are collectively referred to as <strong>altcoins</strong>.\n            </p>\n       \n            <p class=\"list-disc list-inside\">\n                Altcoins were created to address the technological and limitations of Bitcoin such as speed and energy usage, experiment with new consensus mechanisms like Proof of Stake (PoS), \n                enable new functionalities such as smart contracts and dApps, and serve specific niches like privacy, stable value, or governance.\n            </p>\n        </section>\n        <br>\n        \n        <section>\n            <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-semibold mb-2\"> The Role of Altcoins in Web3 and the Future</h2>\n                <p>\n                    Altcoins play a vital role in expanding the cryptocurrency ecosystem beyond Bitcoin.\n                    They offer innovation through new technologies, power decentralized applications, support DeFi\n                    and NFTs, and enable blockchain interoperability and governance. By diversifying use cases, altcoins drive adoption\n                    , competition, and continuous improvement within the Web3 space.\n                </p>\n\n            <p>\n                As blockchain technology evolves, altcoins will play increasingly important roles in digital economies and decentralized infrastructure.\n            </p>\n        </section>\n<br><br>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n        <section >\n            <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-semibold mb-4\">Categories of Altcoins</h2>\n\n            <p>\n                Altcoins can be categorized based on their functionality, use cases, and underlying technology. Here is a simple table that places altcoins into different categories:\n            </p>\n\n            <div  class=\"mb-4 indent-4\">\n             <div class=\"overflow-x-auto\">\n    <table class=\"min-w-full rounded-lg shadow-md\">\n      <thead>\n        <tr class=\"bg-gray-600 text-black uppercase text-sm\">\n          <th class=\"py-3 px-4 text-left\">Category</th>\n          <th class=\"py-3 px-4 text-left\">Examples</th>\n          <th class=\"py-3 px-4 text-left\">Use Cases</th>\n        </tr>\n      </thead>\n      <tbody class=\"text-gray-400\">\n\n        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4 font-medium\">Stablecoins</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Tether (USDT), USD Coin (USDC), Binance USD (BUSD)</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Stable trading, remittances, DeFi stability</td>\n        </tr>\n\n        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4 font-medium\">Utility Tokens</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Chainlink (LINK), Filecoin (FIL), Basic Attention Token (BAT)</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Platform services and access</td>\n        </tr>\n\n        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4 font-medium\">Security Tokens</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">RWA tokens</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Digital representation of real-world assets under regulatory compliance</td>\n        </tr>\n\n        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4 font-medium\">Governance Tokens</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Uniswap (UNI), Maker (MKR), Aave (AAVE)</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">DAO voting and decision-making</td>\n        </tr>\n\n        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4 font-medium\">Privacy Coins</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Monero (XMR), Zcash (ZEC), Dash (DASH)</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Anonymous transactions</td>\n        </tr>\n\n        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4 font-medium\">Meme Coins</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Dogecoin (DOGE), Shiba Inu (SHIB)</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Tipping, community engagement, speculative trading</td>\n        </tr>\n\n        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4 font-medium\">Platform Coins</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">Ethereum (ETH), Cardano (ADA), Solana (SOL)</td>\n          <td class=\"py-3 px-4\">dApps, smart contracts, NFT platforms</td>\n        </tr>\n\n      </tbody>\n    </table>\n  </div>\n\n            </div>\n        </section>\n<br><br>\n        <section>\n            <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-semibold mb-2\">Some popular Altcoins and their applications</h2>\n            <p>\n                Here are some of the most popular altcoins and their primary applications:  \n            </p>    \n            <div class=\"mb-4 indent-4\">\n                <ul class=\"list-disc list-inside\">\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Ethereum (ETH):</strong> The first platform to introduce smart contracts, enabling decentralized applications (dApps) and decentralized finance (DeFi).\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Binance Coin (BNB):</strong> Initially created as a utility token for the Binance exchange, it now powers the Binance Smart Chain for dApps and DeFi.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Cardano (ADA):</strong> A blockchain platform focused on sustainability, scalability, and interoperability, supporting smart contracts and dApps.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Solana (SOL):</strong> Known for its high throughput and low transaction costs, Solana is a platform for fast dApps and DeFi projects.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Polkadot (DOT):</strong> A multi-chain network that enables different blockchains to interoperate, facilitating cross-chain applications.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Ripple (XRP):</strong> Designed for fast and low-cost international money transfers, Ripple aims to revolutionize cross-border payments.\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Chainlink (LINK):</strong> A decentralized oracle network that connects smart contracts with real-world data, enhancing their functionality.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Uniswap (UNI):</strong> A leading decentralized exchange (DEX) that allows users to trade cryptocurrencies directly from their wallets without intermediaries.\n\n                    </li>   \n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Dogecoin (DOGE):</strong> Originally created as a meme, Dogecoin has gained popularity for tipping and community engagement, with a strong online following.    \n                    </li>   \n\n                    <li>\n\n                        <strong>Litecoin (LTC):</strong> Often referred to as the silver to Bitcoin\'s gold, Litecoin is a peer-to-peer cryptocurrency designed for fast transactions.   \n                    </li>\n                </ul>\n        </section>\n\n        <br><br>\n\n        <section>\n             <div class=\"rounded-lg shadow-md\">\n                    <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold mb-4\">Advantages of Altcoins</h2>\n                    <ul class=\"list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 text-base\">\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Lower Entry Barriers:</strong> Altcoins often have a lower price per coin, making them more accessible to new and small-scale investors.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Broader Use Cases:</strong> Many altcoins are designed to serve specific functions—ranging from decentralized finance (DeFi) and smart contracts to privacy, gaming, and storage solutions.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Faster Technological Innovation:</strong> Altcoins push the boundaries of blockchain development by experimenting with new features and frameworks beyond what Bitcoin offers.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>Higher Growth Potential:</strong> Being relatively new or undervalued, some altcoins offer substantial room for price appreciation and adoption.\n                    </li>\n                    <li>\n                        <strong>More Sustainable Consensus Models:</strong> Unlike Bitcoin\'s energy-intensive Proof of Work (PoW), many altcoins use energy-efficient models like Proof of Stake (PoS), reducing environmental impact.\n                    </li>\n                    </ul>\n  </div>\n        </section>\n<br><br>\n        <section>\n\n               <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold mb-4\">Risks and challenges of Altcoins</h1>\n\n                <p>Altcoins offer innovation and investment opportunities, but they also come with significant risks and challenges that users, investors, and developers must carefully consider.</p>\n\n                <h2><strong>1. High Volatility</strong></h2>\n                <p>Altcoin prices can fluctuate dramatically within short periods due to low liquidity, speculative trading, and market sentiment. This makes them high-risk assets, especially for inexperienced investors.</p>\n\n                <h2><strong>2. Lack of Regulation</strong></h2>\n                <p>The regulatory landscape for altcoins is still evolving. Many projects operate in a legal gray area, making them susceptible to sudden bans, restrictions, or lawsuits, which can severely impact their value or usability.</p>\n\n                <h2><strong>3. Security Vulnerabilities</strong></h2>\n                <p>Altcoins, especially those from newer or less-experienced teams, may have exploitable code. Hacks, smart contract bugs, or poor security practices can lead to significant financial loss for users and investors.</p>\n\n                <h2><strong>4. Scams and Fraudulent Projects</strong></h2>\n                <p>With low barriers to entry, it\'s easy to launch altcoins without real utility. Pump-and-dump schemes, rug pulls, and fake ICOs have become common, leading to erosion of trust and investor losses.</p>\n\n                <h2><strong>5. Lack of Liquidity</strong></h2>\n                <p>Many altcoins are traded on fewer exchanges with limited volume. This makes it harder to buy or sell large amounts without significantly impacting the price, leading to slippage and poor trade execution.</p>\n\n                <h2><strong>6. Unproven Technology</strong></h2>\n                <p>Some altcoins use experimental consensus mechanisms or features that haven\'t been thoroughly tested at scale. As a result, they may face unexpected technical failures or require costly upgrades.</p>\n\n                <h2><strong>7. Market Saturation and Competition</strong></h2>\n                <p>The altcoin space is crowded, with thousands of coins competing for user adoption and capital. Most projects struggle to gain traction, and many eventually fade into obscurity or become abandoned.</p>\n\n                <h2><strong>8. Short Project Lifespans</strong></h2>\n                <p>A large percentage of altcoins are not maintained long-term. Teams may lose funding, shift focus, or dissolve, leaving holders with worthless or unsupported tokens.</p>\n\n                <h2><strong>9. Dependence on Community and Hype</strong></h2>\n                <p>Many altcoins derive their value from active communities or social media hype rather than utility or adoption. This makes them vulnerable to rapid sentiment shifts and price crashes.</p>\n\n                <h2><strong>Conclusion</strong></h2>\n                <p>Altcoins present exciting opportunities, but they are not without significant risks. Investors and users should conduct thorough research, diversify cautiously, and remain informed about market trends and project fundamentals. Understanding the potential pitfalls is essential for navigating the fast-evolving altcoin landscape responsibly.</p>\n\n        </section>\n\n<br><br>\n <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> ALTs HEADSUP </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n\n          Altcoins represent innovation, experimentation, and expansion in the cryptocurrency space.\n                While Bitcoin laid the foundation, altcoins push the boundaries of what blockchain technology can do.\n                Whether you\'re investing, building, or learning, understanding altcoins is essential to staying informed in the crypto world.\n         \n\n </div>\n<br><br>\n\n         <section>\n            <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-semibold mb-2\"> Investing in Altcoins</h2>\n              <div class=\" dark:bg-gray-900 \">\n    <p class=\"text-base leading-relaxed\">\n      Before investing in altcoins, it\'s important to approach with careful analysis and strategy. Consider the following key steps:\n    </p>\n\n    <ul class=\"list-disc list-inside space-y-3 text-base\">\n      <li>\n        <strong>Evaluate the Project Team and Vision:</strong> Investigate the experience, credibility, and transparency of the development team. A strong, active team is often a good indicator of a project\'s long-term potential.\n      </li>\n      <li>\n        <strong>Read the Whitepaper and Understand the Tokenomics:</strong> Study the project’s goals, utility, supply distribution, and economic model to assess its real-world value and sustainability.\n      </li>\n      <li>\n        <strong>Analyze Market Capitalization and Trading Volume:</strong> Look beyond price—high market cap and strong trading volume often indicate healthy investor interest and liquidity.\n      </li>\n      <li>\n        <strong>Prioritize Security and Transparency:</strong> Ensure the project follows strong security protocols, has undergone audits, and communicates openly with its community.\n      </li>\n      <li>\n        <strong>Diversify Your Portfolio:</strong> Spread your investment across multiple credible projects to minimize risk and avoid overexposure to any single token.\n      </li>\n      <li>\n        <strong>Use Reputable Exchanges:</strong> Only buy and trade altcoins on trusted, secure, and well-regulated cryptocurrency exchanges to protect your assets.\n      </li>\n    </ul>\n\n  </div>\n\n        </section>\n\n        <br><br>\n\n    </div>\n', 'Altcoins', NULL, 'What does the term \"Altcoin\" refer to in cryptocurrency?', 'All cryptocurrencies other than Bitcoin', 'Bitcoin forks only', 'Coins with no real utility', 'Government-backed digital currencies'),
(45, 7, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which altcoin is known for introducing smart contracts and enabling dApps?', 'Ethereum (ETH)', 'Litecoin (LTC)', 'Ripple (XRP)', 'Dogecoin (DOGE)'),
(46, 7, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is a common use case of stablecoins like USDT and USDC?', 'Maintaining a stable trading value', 'Providing anonymous transactions', 'Mining efficiency', 'Cross-chain interoperability'),
(47, 7, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of the following is a major risk associated with altcoin investments?', 'High price volatility', 'Guaranteed profits', 'Government backing', 'No technical innovation'),
(48, 7, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What does Proof of Stake (PoS) aim to improve over Bitcoin\'s model?', 'Energy efficiency', 'Transaction irreversibility', 'Centralized governance', 'Hardware compatibility'),
(49, 7, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is one of the recommended practices when investing in altcoins?', 'Diversify your portfolio', 'Invest all in one coin', 'Ignore the team and whitepaper', 'Focus only on hype coins'),
(50, 8, '<p>The first action after understanding the foundation of cryptocurrency is to create  and secure your wallet;\n  As said earlier, a wallet is a digital tool that allows you to store, send, and receive cryptocurrencies.\n  There are two main types of wallets, the software wallets (mobile or desktop applications), and\n  hardware wallets (physical devices).</p>\n\n  <p>As a beginner, it is recommended to start with a software wallet for ease of use; The most popular software wallets\n  include MetaMask, Trust Wallet, and Coinbase Wallet.</p>\n  \n  <br><br>\n\n  <h2><strong>Step 1: Choose a Wallet</strong></h2>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 list-inside \">\n    <li>Research and select a wallet that suits your needs ( For this guide, we will use Trustwallet as an example).</li>\n    <li>There are varieties of wallets on different platforms which includes the Mobile, Desktop, and Web versions,\n    the mobile is installed on your phone as an application, the Desktop is installed on your computer, and the Web version is accessed through your web browser.</li>\n    <li>It is important to choose a wallet that is compatible with the cryptocurrencies you plan to use.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br><br>\n\n  <h2><strong>Step 2: Download and Install</strong></h2>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 indent-4 list-inside\">\n    <li>Download and install the Trustwallet application from the app store or the official website.</li>\n    <li>For mobile wallets, search for \"Trust Wallet\" in your app store (Google Play Store for Android or Apple App Store for iOS).</li>\n    <li>For desktop wallets, visit the official Trust Wallet website and download the appropriate version for your operating system (Windows, macOS, or Linux).</li>\n    <li>You can also download your wallets as an Extension on desktop browsers.</li>\n    <li>Ensure you download the official version to avoid scams or phishing attempts.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br><br>\n\n  <h2><strong>Step 3: Create a New Wallet</strong></h2>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 indent-4 list-inside\">\n    <li>Follow the instructions to create a new wallet.</li>\n    <li>This involves setting up a password and generating a recovery phrase.</li>\n    <li>Open the Trust Wallet app and select \"Create a New Wallet.\"</li>\n    <li>Read and accept the terms of service.</li>\n    <li>Set a strong password for your wallet. This password will be used to access your wallet and authorize transactions.</li>\n    <li>After setting the password, you will be presented with a recovery phrase (also known as a seed phrase).</li>\n    <li>Write down the recovery phrase in the correct order and store it securely.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br><br>\n\n  <h2><strong>Step 4: Secure Your Wallet</strong></h2>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 indent-4 list-inside\">\n    <li>Write down your recovery phrase and store it in a safe place. This phrase is crucial for recovering your wallet if you lose access,\n    and must never be shared with anyone (This is very very important!).</li>\n    <li>Do not store your recovery phrase digitally or online, as this can expose it to hackers.</li>\n    <li>Enable two-factor authentication (2FA) if available for added security.</li>\n    <li>Familiarize yourself with the wallet\'s security features, such as biometric authentication or PIN codes.</li>\n    <li>Always keep your wallet software updated to protect against vulnerabilities.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br><br>\n\n  <h2><strong>Step 5: Fund Your Wallet</strong></h2>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 indent-4 list-inside\">\n    <li>To start using your wallet, you need to add some cryptocurrency. The process to buying and adding crypto to your wallet will be dicussed in subsequent lessons.</li>\n  </ol>\n\n  <br><br>\n\n\n  <h2><strong>To send cryptocurrency, you will need the recipient\'s wallet address.</strong></h2>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 indent-4 list-inside\">\n    <li>Open your wallet app and navigate to the \"Send\" section.</li>\n    <li>Enter the recipient\'s wallet address, the amount you want to send, and any additional details required.</li>\n    <li>Review the transaction details and confirm the transaction.</li>\n    <li>Depending on the wallet, you may need to enter your password or use biometric authentication to authorize the transaction.</li>\n    <li>After confirming, the transaction will be processed, and you will receive a notification once it is completed.</li>\n    <li>You may be required to pay a transaction fee, which varies based on the network congestion and the cryptocurrency being sent.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br>\n  <br>\n\n\n  <h2><strong>Anytime you want to recieve cryptocurrency, you will share your wallet address with the sender.</strong></h2>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 indent-4 list-inside\">\n    <li>Open your wallet app and navigate to the \"Receive\" section.</li>\n    <li>Select the cryptocurrency you want to receive on the appropriate network (e.g., Ethereum, Bitcoin, etc.).</li>\n    <li>You will see your wallet address displayed as a string of characters or a QR code.</li>\n    <li>Copy your wallet address or scan the QR code provided.</li>\n    <li>Share this address with the person sending you cryptocurrency.</li>\n    <li>You can also buy cryptocurrency directly within the wallet app using a credit card or bank transfer, depending on the wallet\'s features and supported services.</li>\n    <li>You can purchase cryptocurrency from exchanges like Binance, Coinbase, or Kraken and transfer it to your wallet.</li>\n    <li>Follow the instructions on the exchange to deposit funds into your wallet address.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br><br>\n\n\n\n  <h2><strong>Note:</strong></h2>\n<ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 space-y-1 list-inside\">\n    <li>Your wallet is like your bank account, while your wallet address is like your account number and can be shared with anybody.</li>\n    <li>Always double-check the wallet address before sending or receiving cryptocurrency to avoid mistakes, as transactions are irreversible.</li>\n    <li>Keep your wallet software updated to ensure you have the latest security features and improvements.</li>\n    <li>Copy (with Pen and paper in the right order), and protect your security/seed phrase from other people, as it is the key to your wallet, anybody that has it can take your crypto.</li>\n    <li>Be cautious of phishing attempts and only download wallet software from official sources.</li>\n    <li>You can buy cryptocurrency from exchanges like Binance, Coinbase, or Kraken and transfer it to your wallet.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br><br>\n\n\n  <p>This guide provides a basic overview of how to create and secure a cryptocurrency wallet using Trust Wallet as an example.</p>\n  <p>For more detailed instructions, refer to the official documentation of any wallet you plan to use.</p>\n  <p>This guide might look bulky and exhaustive on paper, but this processes comes simpler and naturally as they are just a few button clicks in practise.</p>\n', 'Getting started with wallets', NULL, 'What is the primary function of a cryptocurrency wallet?', 'To store, send, and receive cryptocurrencies', 'To buy mining equipment', 'To convert crypto to fiat', 'To monitor exchange rates'),
(51, 8, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of the following is an example of a software wallet?', 'Trust Wallet', 'Ledger Nano S', 'Paper wallet', 'USB flash drive'),
(52, 8, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Why should you never store your recovery phrase digitally?', 'It can be exposed to hackers', 'It will get deleted automatically', 'It slows down your wallet', 'It is not compatible with mobile wallets'),
(53, 8, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What should you do after downloading a wallet app?', 'Create a new wallet and write down the recovery phrase', 'Send crypto to a random address', 'Ignore setup instructions', 'Share the wallet with a friend'),
(54, 8, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which section of the wallet app is used to receive cryptocurrency?', 'Receive', 'Send', 'History', 'Buy'),
(55, 8, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is one way to fund your crypto wallet?', 'Transfer from an exchange like Binance or Coinbase', 'Mail cash to the wallet provider', 'Use a prepaid phone card', 'Install more apps on your phone'),
(56, 9, '<p>\n  \nFrom the previous lesson, you created an empty wallet that contains no crypto asset yet. Crypto assets can be gotten if somebody sends it to you using your wallet address, or you buy it with fiat from a crypto exchange and sends it to your wallet address.\n<br>\n\nBefore you proceed to buying and managing crypto , you have to be equiped with the knowledge to safely use your wallet.\n\n</p>\n<br><br>\n\n\n\n  <h2><strong>Common mistakes that beginners make</strong></h2>\n  <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside space-y-2  indent-4\">\n    <li>\n      <strong>Not backing up wallet seed phrase:</strong>\n      Losing your recovery/seed phrase means permanent loss of access. Storing it digitally (e.g., screenshots or cloud notes) makes it vulnerable to hacks, always write it down on paper as soon as you can and store it securely.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Sharing private keys or seed phrases:</strong>\n      Your seed phrase is like a master key, anyone with it can steal your funds. Never share it, even if someone claims to be \"Support\" or \"Admin\", which is a common stealing tactic on the social media platform X(formerly Twitter).\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Falling for scams and phishing:</strong>\n      Fake wallet apps, websites, or giveaway scams are common. Always verify URLs and avoid clicking links in DMs or emails.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Investing without research (FOMO):</strong>\n      Many beginners are in a hurry to make money, so they buy coins just because they are trending or hyped in a fear of missing out on the gains they imagined,this leads to wrong decision making. You need to stay calm, research and understand a project’s utility, team, and risks.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Sending funds to the wrong address or network:</strong>\n      Crypto transactions are irreversible. Sending to the wrong address or incompatible network leads to permanent loss. Changing a single character in an address will result to loss of funds.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Investing more than they can afford to lose:</strong>\n      Crypto markets are volatile. Never invest emotionally or with money you can\'t afford to lose, previous performance of any token is not guarantee that it has a good future, because the crypto ecosystem is dynamic.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Not understanding network fees:</strong>\n      Some networks have high gas fees, so unneccesarily transfering assets from one wallet to another is a good way to lose money. Always check the fees before making transactions, consider using networks with lower fees for smaller transactions, and avoid making transactions that are not necessary.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Leaving funds on exchanges:</strong>\n      Centralized exchanges can be hacked or they can freeze withdrawals. Withdraw to a secure wallet if you are not actively trading or you plan to hold for a long time. Always use reputable exchanges and enable two-factor authentication (2FA) for added security.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Ignoring security best practices:</strong>\n            Not using 2FA or weak/reused passwords puts your assets at risk.\n    </li>\n    <li>\n      <strong>Not understanding taxes or legal requirements:</strong>\n        In some countries and region, Crypto may be taxable. Beginners often do not track transactions, which may cause issues later.\n    </li>\n  </ol>\n\n<br><br>\n\n\n<div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> PHISHING SCAM </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n      Phishing is a common tactic used by scammers to trick users into revealing sensitive information, such as private keys or seed phrases.\n    </p>\n      <br>\n    <p>\n      It involves scammers creating fake versions of popular websites, and deceiving users into entering their credentials or wallet information on their fraudulent platforms. for example, \"<b>https://metamask.io</b>\" is the official website of MetaMask, but a phishing site might look like \"<b>https://metamask-secure.com</b>\" or \"<b>https://metamask-login.com</b>\", they will be designed to look exactly like the original site, but they are not and are only meant to steal your information.\n    </p>\n      <br>\n      <p>\n          Always verify URLs, avoid clicking on suspicious links, and never share your private keys or seed phrases with anyone.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n      <p>if you receive an email claiming to be from your wallet provider asking you to \"verify your account\" by entering your seed phrase, it\'s likely a phishing attempt. Legitimate services will never ask for your seed phrase.</p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n', 'Safety', NULL, 'What is the safest way to store your wallet\'s seed phrase?', 'Write it down on paper and store it securely', 'Take a screenshot and upload to the cloud', 'Send it to your email inbox', 'Memorize it and tell a friend for backup'),
(57, 9, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is a common phishing tactic in the crypto space?', 'Creating fake websites that mimic real ones', 'Offering discounts for verified users', 'Providing hardware wallets for free', 'Blocking your wallet for maintenance'),
(58, 9, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Why is it risky to leave funds on centralized exchanges?', 'They can be hacked or freeze withdrawals', 'You will be charged higher gas fees', 'You cannot send crypto from exchanges', 'They do not support 2FA authentication'),
(59, 9, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What mistake do beginners make due to FOMO?', 'Investing without research based on hype', 'Avoiding wallet creation', 'Using only one exchange', 'Mining instead of buying crypto'),
(60, 9, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Why must you double-check wallet addresses before sending funds?', 'Crypto transactions are irreversible', 'It helps improve wallet speed', 'You can cancel it later if wrong', 'To qualify for staking rewards'),
(61, 9, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is the danger of sharing your private key or seed phrase?', 'Someone can steal all your funds', 'It disables 2FA', 'It slows down your wallet', 'You won’t be able to receive coins'),
(62, 10, '\n <p>\n  <br>\n  Crypto is not like traditional banking where you can call customer support to reverse a transaction or recover lost funds, \n  so it is crucial to understand how best to manage your assets and protect yourself from losses.\n  <br>\n  Crypto assets are primarily traded on two platforms, which are centralized and decentralized platforms.\n  <br>\n  Centralized platforms are those that require you to deposit your assets into their custody, while they handle and process your transactions, while decentralized platforms allow you to retain full control of your assets in your wallet , while making transactions.\n  \n  <br><br>\n\n  In this lesson we will talk about the decentralized platforms, and by the end you should have a solid understanding of decentralized exchanges and how to use them.\n  <br>\n  Let\'s get started!\n  <br>\n </p>\n<br>\n<br>\n\n\n<h2>Decentralized Exchange</h2>\n    \n <p>\n     In the context of crypto asset management, decentralization removes reliance on intermediaries and focuses on user autonomy.\n     <br>\n     As an analogy, decentralization simply means having all your money at hand and under your control without depositing into any bank and allowing them decide the terms of your expenses, or question your monetary activities; You have full control, so basically you have your asset in your wallet, can send or receive tokens, and have the freedom to interact with web3 applications.\n      <br>\n    </p>\n\n<p>\n\n      A decentralized exchange (DEX), is a platform that allows you to trade cryptocurrencies directly from your wallet without the need for a central authority or intermediary. DEXs operate on blockchain technology, enabling peer-to-peer transactions, and while still letting you maintain 100% control over your funds.\n      <br>\n\n      To trade on a DEX, you simply visit their website or download their applications, connect your wallet, select the tokens you want to trade, sign and execute the transaction. The process is automated through smart contracts, which handles the trade execution and settlement.\n      <br>\n    </p>\n   \n<br>\n<br>\n  <h2> <strong>Decentralized trading (Swapping)</strong></h2>\n\n  <p>Decentralized exchanges (DEXs) are a key component of this ecosystem, allowing users to trade cryptocurrencies directly from their wallets without relinquishing custody to a third party.Trading on DEXs is known as swapping, platforms like Uniswap, PancakeSwap, and SushiSwap operate using smart contracts deployed on public blockchains, all you have to do is connect your wallet, and sign transactions to buy or sell tokens.\n  </p> \n\n  <br><br>\n\n   <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> SWAPPING </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n      Swapping is the process of exchanging one cryptocurrency for another directly on a decentralized exchange (DEX). Unlike traditional exchanges, DEXs allow users to trade directly from their wallets. This process is facilitated by smart contracts that automate the trade execution, ensuring transparency and security.\n      <br>\n      <br>\n      In real sense, swapping is basically buying and selling happening simultaneously, what matters is the final token you have after the transactions.\n      <br>\n      <b><i>For example, </i></b>if you swap 1 ETH for 200 USDT, you are effectively selling 1 ETH and buying 200 USDT. Conversely, if you swap 200 USDT for 1 ETH, you are selling 200 USDT and buying 1 ETH.\n      <br>\n    </p>\n   </div>\n\n   <br>\n   <br>\n\n  <p><strong>Key aspects of Decentralized exchanges include:</strong></p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Peer-to-peer trading:</strong> Users can interact directly with each other via automated protocols, without intermediaries.</li>\n    <li><strong>Smart contracts:</strong>All trading logic and asset swaps are governed by transparent, tamper-proof code rather than human administrators.</li>\n    <li><strong>User custody:</strong> Traders will retain full control over their  assets throughout the entire process.</li>\n    <li><strong>Open-source transparency:</strong> Many DEX platforms are built on open-source software, allowing public audits and community contributions.</li>\n  </ul>\n  <br>\n\n  <p>By decentralizing exchange infrastructure, DEXs minimize the risks of hacks, fund freezes, and market manipulation that are more prevalent in centralized systems.</p>\n\n  <br><br>\n\n  <h2><strong>Benefits of trading on DEXs</strong></h2>\n  \n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Self-sovereignty:</strong> Users have complete ownership and control of their digital assets.</li>\n\n    <li><strong>Reduced counterparty risk:</strong> Since no third party holds the assets, there\'s no risk of loss due to institutional failure.</li>\n\n    <li><strong>Global accessibility:</strong> Anyone with internet access and a supported wallet can participate, regardless of geographic location or financial background.</li>\n\n    <li><strong>Interoperability:</strong> Decentralized finance (DeFi) protocols allow users to lend, borrow, stake, and earn yields directly from their wallets without needing a bank or asset manager.</li>\n  <li>\n    <strong>Governance and Community Participation : </strong>\n    As an investor in any governance token, having your tokens decentralized in your wallet allows you to vote on key proposals such as upgrades, funds allocation, and strategic directions.\n  </li>\n  </ul>\n\n  \n\n\n  <br><br>\n  <h2>  <strong>Challenges of DEX trading</strong> </h2>\n  <p>While powerful, DEXs also have some challenges associated with it:</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>User responsibility:</strong> Without custodians, users are fully accountable for their security; Mistakes means an irreversible loss of funds.</li>\n\n    <li><strong>Complex interfaces:</strong> Some DEX platforms lack the user-friendliness of centralized ones, which can deter newcomers;However, DEXs are getting simplified everyday.</li>\n\n    <li><strong>Scalability and speed:</strong> Decentralized networks may experience congestion and high transaction fees during peak demand.</li>\n\n    <li><strong>Regulatory uncertainty:</strong> The decentralized nature of these platforms makes it difficult for regulators to apply traditional frameworks, which can lead to legal ambiguity.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <br><br>\n\n  <p>As blockchain technology continues to evolve, DEXs will remain central to its progress, offering a platform where users have full control and do not have to expose their personal data to make a simple trade.</p>\n\n\n\n', 'Decentralized Exchange(DEX)', NULL, 'What is a key feature of a decentralized exchange (DEX)?', 'It allows peer-to-peer trading without intermediaries', 'It requires users to deposit funds into a bank', 'It uses human administrators for trades', 'It limits users from accessing their assets'),
(63, 10, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What does swapping mean on a DEX?', 'Exchanging one cryptocurrency for another', 'Sending funds to a centralized platform', 'Minting new coins from your wallet', 'Backing up wallet data to the cloud'),
(64, 10, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of the following is a benefit of using a DEX?', 'Users maintain full control of their digital assets', 'It offers 24/7 customer service', 'You must complete KYC before every trade', 'You need to use a bank account for trading'),
(65, 10, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which platforms are examples of decentralized exchanges?', 'Uniswap, PancakeSwap, and SushiSwap', 'Binance, Kraken, and Coinbase', 'Visa, MasterCard, and PayPal', 'Trust Wallet, MetaMask, and Ledger'),
(66, 10, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is a challenge users may face on a DEX?', 'Complex user interfaces and high network fees', 'Mandatory bank registration', 'Limited token availability', 'No access to smart contracts'),
(67, 10, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What technology powers trades on a decentralized exchange?', 'Smart contracts', 'Central bank protocols', 'Manual approval from admins', 'Cloud-based authentication');
INSERT INTO `questions_and_answers` (`id`, `learning_cycle`, `material`, `material_title`, `lesson_video`, `question`, `answer`, `option_1`, `option_2`, `option_3`) VALUES
(68, 11, '\n  <p>Before diving into trading or buying your first crypto, it\'s also essential to understand what a centralized exchange is, how it works, and what risks and benefits it carries.</p>\n  <br>\n\n  <h2>What is a Centralized Exchange?</h2>\n  <p>A <strong>Centralized Exchange</strong> (CEX) is a <strong>platform operated by a company or organization</strong> that acts as a <strong>middleman</strong> between buyers and sellers of cryptocurrency. These platforms handle all transactions, user accounts, and security on behalf of the users.</p>\n<br>\n  <p>They serve as a bridge between cryptocurrency and traditional finance; Think of it like a bank or a stock exchange. In crypto terms, when you use a CEX, you\'re <strong>trusting the exchange to hold your assets</strong>, keep them safe, and process your trades.</p>\n\n  <p><strong>Popular examples of centralized exchanges are:</strong></p>\n  <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 list-inside\">\n    <li>Binance</li>\n    <li>Coinbase</li>\n    <li>Kraken</li>\n    <li>KuCoin</li>\n    <li>Gate.io</li>\n    <li>OKX</li>\n  </ol>\n  <br>\n\n  <p>These platforms are often the first place new users go to buy or trade cryptocurrencies, because they provide a simple way to buy, sell, and trade digital assets using traditional currencies like USD, EUR, or GBP, also with a user-friendly interface,  and handles all the technical aspects of trading for you.</p>\n  <br><br>\n\n  <h2> <strong>How Do Centralized Exchanges Work </strong></h2>\n\n  <p>Centralized exchanges operate by matching buy and sell orders from users. Here’s a simplified breakdown of how they work:</p>\n  <ol class=\"list-none indent-4  list-inside  space-y-2 \" >\n    <li><strong>Order Matching:</strong> When you place an order to buy or sell crypto, the exchange matches it with another user’s order.</li>\n    <li><strong>Custodial Services:</strong> The exchange holds your crypto in their wallets, managing the private keys for you.</li>\n    <li><strong>Trading Fees:</strong> CEXs charge fees for trades, deposits, and withdrawals, which can vary widely.</li>\n    <li><strong>Security Measures:</strong> They implement various security protocols to protect user funds, but they are still vulnerable to hacks.</li> \n    <li><strong>Regulatory Compliance:</strong> Many CEXs comply with local regulations, requiring KYC (Know Your Customer) verification.</li>\n  </ol>\n  \n\n\n\n  <br>\n  <h2> <strong>Step-by-Step guide to getting started with a CEX </strong></h2>\n\n\n  <p>Using a centralized exchange is generally straightforward. Here’s a step-by-step guide to get you started:</p>\n  <br>\n\n<section class=\"pl-5\">   \n  <h2><strong>1. Choose a Reputable Exchange</strong></h2>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">Start by selecting a well-known and reputable centralized exchange. Look for reviews, security features, and user feedback. Some of the most popular options are listed above.</p>\n  <br>\n  <h2><strong>2. Create an Account</strong></h2>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">Sign up for an account on the exchange. For this you’ll need to provide and verify your email address, and create a strong password.</p>\n  <br>  \n  <h2><strong>3. Complete KYC Verification</strong></h2>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">All exchanges require you to complete KYC (Know Your Customer) verification. This usually involves submitting one of identification documents like a Passport , a driver’s license, National identity document, or a bank issued number,  and sometimes a proof of address; All this are done in compliance with government laws and measures against money laundering.</p>\n  <br>\n  <h2><strong>4. Secure Your Account</strong></h2>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">Enable two-factor authentication (2FA) for added security. This adds an extra layer of protection to your account, making it harder for unauthorized users to access it.</p>\n  <br>\n  <h2><strong>5. Deposit Funds</strong></h2>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">Once your account is set up, you can deposit funds. Most exchanges allow you to deposit fiat currency (like USD, EUR, etc.) via bank transfer, credit card, or other payment methods like P2P. They also accept cryptocurrency deposits if you already own crypto.</p>  \n  <br>\n\n  <h2><strong>6. Start Trading</strong></h2>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">With funds in your account, you can start trading. You can buy or sell various cryptocurrencies by placing orders on the exchange. You can choose between market orders (buy/sell at current market price) or limit orders (set a specific price for buying/selling).</p>\n  <br>\n  <h2><strong>7. Withdraw Funds</strong></h2>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">After trading, you can withdraw your funds. If you want to take your crypto off the exchange, you can transfer it to your personal wallet. If you want to cash out, you can withdraw fiat currency back to your bank account.</p>\n  <br>\n  <h2><strong>8. Monitor Your Account</strong></h2>\n  <p class=\"pl-5\">Regularly check your account for any updates, security alerts, or changes in policies. It’s also a good idea to keep track of your trades and balances.</p>\n\n</section>\n<br>\n\n\n  <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> CUSTODIANSHIP: WHO HOLDS MY CRYPTO </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n       <p>When you use a CEX, your crypto is stored by the exchange, not in your personal wallet. You don’t hold your private keys, meaning if the exchange is hacked or closes down, you might lose access.</p>\n       <br>\n  <p>This leads to the saying: <strong>“Not your keys, not your coins.”</strong></p>\n  </div>\n  <br><br>\n  \n  \n\n\n  <h2> <strong>Benefits of Using Centralized Exchanges</strong>  </h2>\n  <br>\n    <p>Centralized exchanges offer several advantages that make them appealing to both new and experienced traders. below are some of these benefits:</p>\n    <br>\n    <section class=\"pl-5\">\n    <h3><strong>1. User-Friendly Interface</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Centralized exchanges (CEXs) are designed with simplicity in mind, making them ideal for beginners. Most offer clean dashboards, mobile apps, and guided features like instant buy/sell buttons. This makes it easy to start trading without needing to understand the complex technical details of blockchain technology.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>2. High Liquidity</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Liquidity refers to how easily an asset can be bought or sold without causing a major change in its price. Centralized exchanges usually have a large number of users and trading volume, which means you can execute trades quickly and at stable prices — especially important for assets with high demand.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>3. Fiat Support</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Most CEXs allow users to fund their accounts using traditional (fiat) currencies like USD, EUR, or NGN. This means you can buy crypto directly using your debit card, bank transfer, or mobile money, a convenience not always available on decentralized platforms.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>4. Customer Support</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">If you run into issues like a failed transaction, login problems, or delays in withdrawal, centralized exchanges typically provide customer support via live chat, email, or help tickets. This level of service is especially helpful for users who are not technically inclined.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>5. Advanced Trading Tools</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">For more experienced users, centralized platforms often offer sophisticated tools such as:</p>\n    <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 list-inside space-y-2\">\n        <li>Real-time charts</li>\n        <li>Limit and stop orders</li>\n        <li>Futures and margin trading</li>\n        <li>API access for bots</li>\n    </ol>\n    <p class=\"pl-5\">These tools make it easier to implement complex trading strategies and monitor the market effectively.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>6. Security Infrastructure</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Top-tier centralized exchanges invest heavily in security. They use advanced measures like:</p>\n    <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 list-inside space-y-2\">\n        <li>Two-Factor Authentication (2FA)</li>\n        <li>Cold wallet storage</li>\n        <li>Regular security audits</li>\n    </ol>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">While no system is completely risk-free, these platforms typically offer stronger protective infrastructure than individual users managing their own wallets.</p>\n    <br>\n    <h3><strong>7. Regulatory Compliance</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Many centralized exchanges comply with local regulations, which can provide an added layer of trust. They often require KYC (Know Your Customer) verification, which helps prevent fraud and money laundering. This compliance can also make it easier to resolve disputes or recover lost funds.</p>\n    </section>\n  <br><br>\n\n  <h2><strong> Risks and Downsides of Centralized Exchanges</strong></h2>\n  <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>1. Lack of Full Control</strong>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">On centralized exchanges, you don’t own your private keys, the exchange does. This means you rely entirely on the platform to access and manage your funds.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>2. Security Breaches</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Exchanges are common targets for hackers due to the large volume of funds they hold. If hacked, users can lose their assets, often with little chance of recovery.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>3. Regulatory Risks</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Governments can suddenly change crypto regulations. This may lead to account freezes, trading bans, or forced shutdowns of exchanges, especially in certain regions.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>4. Withdrawal Restrictions</strong></h3>\n    <p  class=\"pl-4\">Exchanges may impose limits on how much you can withdraw daily. Delays or freezes can also occur during system issues, audits, or flagged account activity.</p>\n    <br>\n\n    <h3><strong>5. Custodial Risk</strong></h3>\n    <p class=\"pl-4\">Your assets are held by the exchange, and mismanagement, fraud, or bankruptcy (like the FTX case) can result in total loss of funds, with no guaranteed compensation.</p>\n\n<br><br>\n\n  <p>Centralized exchanges are an essential entry point for most crypto beginners. They offer convenience, ease of use, and access to fiat on-ramps, all crucial for getting started.</p>\n  <p>However, as you grow in the crypto space, you will understand their limitations and gradually explore decentralized options where you can own and safely manage your assets.</p>\n  ', 'Centralized Exchanges(CEX)', NULL, 'What does a centralized exchange (CEX) primarily do?', 'Acts as a middleman between buyers and sellers of crypto', 'Allows peer-to-peer decentralized trading', 'Stores crypto in personal wallets', 'Runs only on smart contracts'),
(69, 11, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of these is a well-known centralized exchange?', 'Binance', 'Uniswap', 'Metamask', 'Trust Wallet'),
(70, 11, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is required during the KYC process on most centralized exchanges?', 'Submission of identity documents like passport or ID', 'Only email verification', 'Just a phone number', 'Biometric fingerprint scan'),
(71, 11, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is a key benefit of using centralized exchanges?', 'User-friendly interface for beginners', 'They are unregulated', 'They require no internet connection', 'They do not charge any fees'),
(72, 11, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What does the phrase \'Not your keys, not your coins\' imply?', 'You don’t control your crypto if the exchange holds the keys', 'You should never trade crypto', 'Crypto is free for all', 'Exchanges give out private keys to users'),
(73, 11, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of the following is a common risk of centralized exchanges?', 'Security breaches', 'No access to fiat', 'Unlimited withdrawals', 'Inability to use charts'),
(74, 12, '\n\n    <div class=\" mx-auto p-6\">\n        <section >\n            <h2 class=\"text-xl font-semibold  mb-2\">What is an Order?</h2>\n            <p>An <strong>order</strong> is an instruction you give to the exchange to buy or sell an asset at a specific price and quantity. All trades on centralized exchanges (CEXs) begin with placing an order, which goes into an <strong>order book</strong> where buyers and sellers are matched.</p>\n        </section>\n<br>\n        <section>\n            <h2 class=\"text-xl font-semibold mb-2\">Types of Orders</h2>\n\n            <div class=\"p-4 rounded-lg shadow mb-4\">\n                <h3 class=\"text-lg font-semibold \">1. Market Order</h3>\n                <p class=\"pl-3\">This order executes immediately at the best available price. it is very useful for quick trades, but may experience price slippage.</p>\n            </div>\n\n            <div class=\" p-4 rounded-lg shadow mb-4\">\n                <h3 class=\"text-lg font-semibold \">2. Limit Order</h3>\n                <p class=\"pl-3\">This order lets you set the price and quantity at which you want to buy or sell. The order remains on the book until your set price is attained and your order is matched.</p>\n            </div>\n\n            <div class=\" p-4 rounded-lg shadow mb-4\">\n                <h3 class=\"text-lg font-semibold \">3. Stop Order (Stop-Loss)</h3>\n                <p class=\"pl-3\">This order triggers a market order when the asset hits a specific price. it is widely used to reduce losses or enter trends.</p>\n            </div>\n\n            <div class=\"p-4 rounded-lg shadow\">\n                <h3 class=\"text-lg font-semibold \">4. Stop-Limit Order</h3>\n                <p class=\"pl-3\">Triggers a limit order instead of a market order once the stop price is hit. Offers more control but might not be filled.</p>\n            </div>\n        </section>\n<br>\n\n\n        <section class=\"mb-6\">\n            <h2 class=\"text-xl font-semibold mb-2\">Order duration</h2>\n            <p class=\"pl-3\"> Order duration is simply the lifetime of an order, timed conditions determining if an order will be executed, cancelled or expired. They are classified as :</p>\n\n            <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] list-inside pl-4\">\n                <li><strong>GTC (Good Till Cancelled):</strong> Stays active until filled or manually canceled.</li>\n                <li><strong>IOC (Immediate or Cancel):</strong> Fills what it can instantly, and cancels the rest.</li>\n                <li><strong>FOK (Fill or Kill):</strong> Must fill the entire order immediately or cancel it all.</li>\n            </ol>\n            <br>\n            <p class=\"pl-3\">\n              <b class=\"text-red-300\">NOTE </b> : Orders are auto set to GTC by default, meaning they will remain open until filled or canceled. You can change this setting in your exchange account preferences.\n            </p>\n        </section>\n        <br><br>\n\n        <section class=\"mb-6\">\n              <section >\n            <h2 class=\"text-xl font-semibold mb-2\">Order books</h2>\n            <p>The <strong>order book</strong> is a live record of all open buy and sell orders. Buy orders are called <em>bids</em>, while sell orders are <em>asks</em>. The exchange’s <strong>matching engine</strong> finds matching pairs to execute trades automatically.</p>\n        </section>\n<br>\n\n            <h2 class=\"text-l font-semibold mb-2 \">Sample order book</h2>\n            <div class=\"overflow-x-auto\">\n                <table class=\"w-full text-sm text-left border border-gray-300\">\n                    <thead>\n                        <tr>\n                            <th class=\"px-3 py-2\">Buy Orders (Bids)</th>\n                            <th></th>\n                            <th class=\"px-3 py-2\">Sell Orders (Asks)</th>\n                        </tr>\n                    </thead>\n                    <tbody>\n                        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n                            <td class=\"px-3 py-2\">$29,950 – 0.5 BTC</td>\n                            <td></td>\n                            <td class=\"px-3 py-2\">$30,000 – 0.7 BTC</td>\n                        </tr>\n                        <tr class=\"border-t\">\n                            <td class=\"px-3 py-2\">$29,900 – 1.0 BTC</td>\n                            <td></td>\n                            <td class=\"px-3 py-2\">$30,100 – 1.2 BTC</td>\n                        </tr>\n                    </tbody>\n                </table>\n            </div>\n            <p class=\"mt-2 dark:text-gray-400\">This is a simplified view of an order book. The left side shows buy orders (bids) and the right side shows sell orders (asks). In an exchange, the price and quantity of each order are usually displayed side by side with the order request form <span class=\"text-red-300\"><i><a href=\"#demo_box\">(Demo shown below)</a></i></span></p>\n        </section>\n        <br>\n        <br>\n\n\n\n\n        <section>\n            <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold mb-4\"><strong>Steps to placing an Order</strong></h2>\n        <p>Placing an order on a centralized exchange is straightforward. Follow these steps to ensure your trades are executed correctly:</p>\n        <br>\n       \n        <div class=\" mx-auto\">\n        <!-- Step 1 -->\n            <section class=\"mb-1\">\n                <h2 class=\"text-xl font-semibold mb-2\">1. Choose the asset to trade</h2>\n                <p class=\"pl-3\">Select the cryptocurrency or trading pair you want to trade, such as <strong>BTC/USDT</strong> or <strong>ETH/USDT</strong>. Ensure the market has sufficient liquidity and matches your trading goals.</p>\n            </section>\n            <br>\n\n        <!-- Step 2 -->\n        <section>\n            <h2 class=\"text-xl font-semibold mb-2\">2. Select the order type</h2>\n            <p  class=\"pl-3\">Pick how you want the order to execute:</p>\n            <ol class=\"list-disc list-inside mt-2 pl-3\">\n                <li><strong>Market Order:</strong> Fills immediately at the best available price.</li>\n                <li><strong>Limit Order:</strong> Executes only at your specified price or better.</li>\n                <li><strong>Stop Order:</strong> Triggers when a target price is reached.</li>\n                <li><strong>Stop-Limit Order:</strong> Converts into a limit order after the stop price is hit.</li>\n            </ol>\n        </section>\n        <br>\n\n        <!-- Step 3 -->\n        <section>\n            <h2 class=\"text-xl font-semibold mb-2\">3. Enter price and amount</h2>\n            <p class=\"pl-3\">Enter the <strong>price</strong> (for non-market orders) and the <strong>amount</strong> of the asset you want to buy or sell. Most exchanges will calculate the total cost or proceeds automatically.</p>\n        </section>\n        <br>\n\n        <!-- Step 4 -->\n        <section>\n            <h2 class=\"text-xl font-semibold mb-2\">4. Review order details</h2>\n            <p  class=\"pl-3\">Check all inputs carefully before submitting:</p>\n            <ol class=\"list-none list-inside mt-2 pl-3\">\n                <li>-Buy or Sell side</li>\n                <li>-Order type</li>\n                <li>-Trading pair</li>\n                <li>-Price, amount, and estimated total</li>\n                <li>-Applicable fees</li>\n            </ol>\n        </section>\n        <br>\n\n        <!-- Step 5 -->\n        <section>\n            <h2 class=\"text-xl font-semibold mb-2\">5. Submit and monitor the order</h2>\n            <p class=\"pl-3\">Submit your order. Market orders are executed instantly, while limit and stop orders remain open until filled. Monitor active orders under <strong>\"Open Orders\"</strong> and track filled trades in your order history. You can cancel or adjust unfilled orders if needed.</p>\n        </section>\n        </div>\n\n        </section>\n        <br>\n        <br>\n\n\n        <section>\n            <p> <i></i>   Orders are the backbone of trading on centralized exchanges. Whether you\'re trading as a beginner or an expert, understanding how market, limit, stop, and other types of orders work will give you more control and reduce unnecessary losses. Use the tools provided by your CEX wisely to trade safely and efficiently.           \n            </p>\n           \n        </section>\n    </div>\n<br>\n <br>\n            <p class=\"text-red-500 font-italic text-center\">Note: below is a simple demo order form.</p>\n    <div class=\"max-w-md mx-auto mt-10 p-6 dark:bg-white rounded-xl shadow-md\" id=\"demo_box\">\n        <h2 class=\"text-xl font-bold mb-4 text-center\">  Place order  <span class=\"text-blue-500\"><b> (DEMO) </b> </span>  </h2>\n\n        <form method=\"POST\" class=\"space-y-4\">\n\n            <!-- Order Side: Buy or Sell -->\n            <div class=\"flex justify-between bg-gray-100 p-2 rounded-lg\">\n                <label class=\"w-1/2 text-center\">\n                    <input type=\"radio\" name=\"side\" value=\"buy\" class=\"hidden peer\" checked>\n                    <div class=\"peer-checked:bg-green-500 peer-checked:text-white p-2 rounded-lg cursor-pointer\">Buy</div>\n                </label>\n                <label class=\"w-1/2 text-center\">\n                    <input type=\"radio\" name=\"side\" value=\"sell\" class=\"hidden peer\">\n                    <div class=\"peer-checked:bg-red-500 peer-checked:text-white p-2 rounded-lg cursor-pointer\">Sell</div>\n                </label>\n            </div>\n\n            <!-- Order Type: Market or Limit -->\n            <div>\n                <label for=\"order_type\" class=\"block text-sm font-medium\">Order Type</label>\n                <select name=\"order_type\" id=\"order_type\" class=\"mt-1 block w-full border-gray-300 rounded-md shadow-sm focus:ring-blue-500 focus:border-blue-500\">\n                    <option value=\"market\">Market</option>\n                    <option value=\"limit\">Limit</option>\n                </select>\n            </div>\n\n            <!-- Trading Pair -->\n            <div>\n                <label for=\"pair\" class=\"block text-sm font-medium\">Trading Pair</label>\n                <select name=\"pair\" id=\"pair\" class=\"mt-1 block w-full border-gray-300 rounded-md shadow-sm focus:ring-blue-500 focus:border-blue-500\">\n                    <option value=\"BTC/USDT\">BTC/USDT</option>\n                    <option value=\"ETH/USDT\">ETH/USDT</option>\n                    <option value=\"BNB/USDT\">BNB/USDT</option>\n                </select>\n            </div>\n\n            <!-- Price Field (for Limit Orders) -->\n            <div>\n                <label for=\"price\" class=\"block text-sm font-medium\">Price (USDT)</label>\n                <input type=\"number\" step=\"0.01\" name=\"price\" id=\"price\" placeholder=\"Enter price\" class=\"mt-1 block w-full border-gray-300 rounded-md shadow-sm focus:ring-blue-500 focus:border-blue-500\">\n            </div>\n\n            <!-- Amount Field -->\n            <div>\n                <label for=\"amount\" class=\"block text-sm font-medium\">Amount (e.g., BTC)</label>\n                <input type=\"number\" step=\"0.0001\" name=\"amount\" id=\"amount\" placeholder=\"Enter amount\" class=\"mt-1 block w-full border-gray-300 rounded-md shadow-sm focus:ring-blue-500 focus:border-blue-500\">\n            </div>\n\n            <!-- Optional: Auto-Calculated Total -->\n            <div>\n                <label for=\"total\" class=\"block text-sm font-medium\">Total (USDT)</label>\n                <input type=\"number\" step=\"0.01\" name=\"total\" id=\"total\" placeholder=\"Auto-calculated or manual\" class=\"mt-1 block w-full border-gray-300 rounded-md shadow-sm focus:ring-blue-500 focus:border-blue-500\">\n            </div>\n\n            <!-- Submit Button -->\n            <div>\n                <button type=\"submit\" class=\"w-full py-2 px-4 bg-blue-600 text-white font-semibold rounded-md hover:bg-blue-700\">Submit Order</button>\n            </div>\n        </form>\n    </div>\n\n', 'Orders', NULL, 'What is a market order in trading?', 'An order that executes immediately at the best available price.', 'An order that waits until a set price is reached before executing.', 'An order that triggers only during specific market hours.', 'An order that stays in the book forever.'),
(75, 12, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which type of order remains open until your set price is reached?', 'Limit Order', 'Market Order', 'Stop Order', 'Immediate or Cancel Order'),
(76, 12, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What happens when a stop price is hit in a stop-limit order?', 'It triggers a limit order.', 'It cancels the trade automatically.', 'It triggers a market order.', 'It converts into a fill-or-kill order.'),
(77, 12, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What does FOK (Fill or Kill) mean in order duration?', 'The entire order must be filled immediately or canceled.', 'Order fills what it can and cancels the rest.', 'Order remains until manually canceled.', 'Order waits for the best price before executing.'),
(78, 12, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'In an order book, what are sell orders called?', 'Asks', 'Bids', 'Limits', 'Stops'),
(79, 12, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which step involves checking the trading pair, price, and fees before submitting an order?', 'Review order details', 'Choose the asset to trade', 'Select the order type', 'Submit the order and monitor it'),
(80, 13, '<div class=\"dark:bg-gray-900 dark:text-gray-400\">\n\n    <div>\n        <h1 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">Preamble</h1>\n        <p>\n            This lesson is a comprehensive guide to understanding cryptocurrency airdrops, their purpose, types, and how to participate safely. It covers everything from the basics of what an airdrop is, to the risks involved, and provides practical tips for users looking to benefit from these promotional distributions.\n\n            <br>\n            Having no funds to directly engage in crypto trading should not deter you from learning about the ecosystem; Airdrops are a great way to get started without any initial investment. They allow you to receive free tokens or coins, which can be used for trading, staking, or simply holding as an investment.\n        </p>\n    </div>\n<br>\n\n\n    <div class=\"mx-auto\">\n        <h1 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">What are Airdrops in cryptocurrency?</h1>\n\n        <p class=\"mb-6\">In the world of cryptocurrency, an <strong>airdrop</strong> refers to the distribution of free tokens or coins to a large number of wallet addresses. This is often done as a promotional strategy by blockchain projects to create awareness, reward users, build a loyal community or as a way to decentralize token ownership.</p>\n\n        <p class=\"mb-6\">Simply put, airdrops are a way to give away free crypto assets to users, either automatically or in exchange for small tasks, in an effort to build engagement and interest in a project.</p>\n    </div>\n\n    <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">Why do crypto projects perform Airdrops?</h2>\n    <p>Airdrops serve several purposes in the cryptocurrency ecosystem, these includes but not limited to:</p>\n    <br>\n    <ol class=\"indent-4 list-[lower-roman] mb-6 list-inside space-y-2\">\n        <li><strong>Marketing and Awareness:</strong> Airdrops create buzz and bring attention to a new crypto project.</li>\n        <li><strong>Rewarding Loyalty:</strong> Existing users or community members are often rewarded for their support.</li>\n        <li><strong>Decentralized Token Distribution:</strong>It serves as a way to spread token ownership across a wide audience.</li>\n        <li><strong>Kickstarting Ecosystems:</strong> Encourages early adoption and use of a platform or blockchain.</li>\n    </ol>\n    \n    <br>\n\n   <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> IMPORTANCE OF AIRDROPS </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n        The importance of airdrops in building a user base cannot be overstated, this importance stems from the fact that money is a shared belief and is only accepted as money because many people(users) believes that it is money or an asset and respects it\'s worth.\n\n        Every new cryptocurrency project aims to establish a user base that believes in its value and potential. Airdrops provide an effective way to achieve this by distributing free tokens to users, thereby incentivizing them to engage with the platform.\n        By receiving tokens, users are more likely to explore the project, participate in its ecosystem, and spread the word to others. This creates a ripple effect, attracting more users and building a community around the project.\n        \n    </p>\n   </div>\n   <br><br>\n\n\n\n    <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">Common types of Airdrops</h2>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        Airdrops can take various forms, each with its own criteria and depending on the goal the developers aim to achieve. Here are some common types of airdrops you might encounter:\n    </p>\n    <br>\n    <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] pl-3 list-inside mb-6 space-y-2\">\n        <li><strong>Standard Airdrop:</strong> Users receive tokens just for signing up or providing their wallet address.</li>\n        <li><strong>Bounty Airdrop:</strong> Users complete specific tasks like sharing posts, joining groups, or creating content.</li>\n        <li><strong>Holder Airdrop:</strong> Tokens are given to holders of another cryptocurrency, such as ETH or a specific token.</li>\n        <li><strong>Exclusive Airdrop:</strong> Sent to selected users, often based on previous involvement with the project.</li>\n        <li><strong>Retroactive Airdrop:</strong> Rewards users who have already interacted with a platform before a certain date.</li>\n    </ol>\n    <br>\n\n\n    <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">How Airdrops work</h2>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">Airdrops typically follow a structured process to ensure fair distribution and engagement. Here’s how they generally work:</p>\n    <ol class=\"list-[lower-roman] pl-3 list-inside mb-6 space-y-2\">\n        <li>The project announces an upcoming airdrop and defines eligibility rules, this is usually done through their social media handles and propagated futhermore by their paid influencers.</li>\n        <li>Users may need to complete tasks such as following social media accounts, joining Telegram groups, or holding specific tokens in their wallets.</li>\n        <li>A snapshot may be taken of the blockchain at a specific time to record wallet balances.</li>\n        <li>Eligible users may need to complete tasks or simply wait to receive the tokens.</li>\n        <li>The tokens are then distributed automatically or made claimable through a link.</li>\n    </ol>\n    <br>\n    <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">How to qualify for Airdrops</h2>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">To qualify for airdrops, users typically need to meet certain criteria which are usually determined by the projects developers, some users can be left out if they don\'t meet those criteria. Here are some common ways to become eligible:</p>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n    <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 list-inside mb-6 space-y-2\">\n        <li>Interact with DeFi platforms, bridges, or testnets.</li>\n        <li>Hold specific tokens or NFTs in non-custodial wallets.</li>\n        <li>Participate early in a protocol’s ecosystem.</li>\n        <li>Stay informed through official project channels and community forums.</li>\n    </ol>\n    <br>\n\n    <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">Classes of Airdrops</h2>\n    <p>\n        Airdrops can also be categorized into different classes based on the tasks performed. Here are some common classes of airdrops:\n    </p>\n    <br>\n    <h4><strong>Testnets</strong></h4>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">Testnets are networks used for testing purposes before launching on the mainnet. Airdrops on testnets reward users who interact with the platform during its development phase.</p>\n    <br>\n    <h4><strong>Retroactive Airdrops</strong></h4>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">Retroactive airdrops reward users who have previously interacted with a platform, even before the official launch. This encourages early adoption and community engagement.</p>\n    <br>    \n    <h4><strong>Yapping</strong></h4>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">Yapping refers to airdrops that require users to engage in social media activities, such as sharing posts, joining groups, or creating content. This helps increase the project\'s visibility and reach.</p>\n    <br>\n    <h4><Strong>DEPIN</Strong></h4>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">DEPIN (Decentralized Physical Infrastructure Networks) airdrops are designed to reward users who contribute to the development of decentralized physical infrastructure. This can include tasks like running nodes, providing resources, or participating in governance.</p>\n    <br>\n    <h4><strong>Mining</strong></h4>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">Mining airdrops are distributed to users who contribute computational power to secure the network. This is common in proof-of-work blockchains, where miners are rewarded with tokens for validating transactions and maintaining the network.</p>\n    <br>\n\n\n\n    <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">Risks and cautions</h2>\n    <ol class=\"list-disc pl-4 list-inside space-y-2 \">\n        <li><strong>Phishing Scams:</strong> Beware of fake airdrops asking for private keys or wallet access.</li>\n        <li><strong>Dusting Attacks:</strong> Some fake tokens may be sent to wallets to track or exploit users.</li>\n        <li><strong>Privacy Risks:</strong> Sharing wallet addresses or linking social media can expose personal data.</li>\n        <li><strong>Tax Liabilities:</strong> Airdropped tokens may be considered taxable income in some jurisdictions.</li>\n    </ol>\n    <br><br>\n\n    <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">Examples of famous Airdrops</h2>\n    <ol class=\"pl-4 list-disc space-y-2 list-inside \">\n        <li><strong>Uniswap (UNI):</strong> Gave away 400 UNI tokens to every wallet that used the platform before a certain date.</li>\n        <li><strong>Arbitrum (ARB):</strong> Rewarded users who interacted with the Arbitrum Layer 2 network.</li>\n        <li><strong>Optimism (OP):</strong> Airdropped tokens to early users of the Optimism ecosystem.</li>\n        <li><strong>Aptos (APT):</strong> Distributed tokens to users who participated in the Aptos testnet.</li>\n        <li><strong>StarkNet (STRK):</strong> Airdropped tokens to users who engaged with the StarkNet Layer 2 solution.</li>\n\n    </ol>\n    <br><br>\n\n    <p>Airdrops offer a unique opportunity to earn free tokens and get involved in early-stage crypto projects. While they can be highly rewarding, users must stay vigilant and protect themselves from scams and malicious actors. By understanding how airdrops work and how to qualify safely, you, traders, and enthusiasts can take advantage of it and earn without any investment capital, just perform the tasks if any and be patient.</p>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n        Airdrops are a good entrance point for crypto enthusiasts who do not have capital for investments.\n    </p>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n        <strong>DISCLAIMER</strong> Always do your own research (DYOR) before participating in airdrops. Only use official channels and never share your private keys or sensitive information with anyone. Airdrops are not guaranteed and may involve risks, including potential loss of funds.\n    </p>\n    <br>\n    <p><a href=\"https://t.me/+9_JSb04pVRsyNjc8\" target=\"_blank\" class=\"text-blue-300\"><i>(Click to join our official airdrops advisory telegram group)</i></a></p>\n\n</div>\n<br>\n    \n    ', 'Airdrops 1', NULL, 'Which of the following is a reason why projects perform airdrops?', 'To encourage early adoption and build community engagement', 'To burn tokens and reduce supply', 'To punish inactive wallet holders', 'To bypass blockchain consensus mechanisms'),
(81, 13, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is the role of a snapshot in an airdrop process?', 'To record wallet balances at a specific point in time', 'To display market trends in charts', 'To update blockchain firmware', 'To create smart contract backups'),
(82, 13, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which class of airdrop is associated with users contributing to physical infrastructure?', 'DEPIN Airdrop', 'Yapping Airdrop', 'Holder Airdrop', 'Retroactive Airdrop'),
(83, 13, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What qualifies someone for a Holder Airdrop?', 'Owning specific cryptocurrencies in their wallet', 'Referring the most users to a platform', 'Sending a minimum amount of ETH to a contract', 'Completing quizzes and surveys'),
(84, 13, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Why are airdrops important in building a user base?', 'They create belief in the value of a new token by distributing it widely', 'They prevent inflation in the crypto economy', 'They reduce validator load on proof-of-stake chains', 'They generate token burning events'),
(85, 13, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of these is an example of an Exclusive Airdrop?', 'Distribution to users based on prior involvement with the project', 'Tokens given randomly to all addresses on Ethereum', 'Rewards for solving puzzles on testnets', 'Tokens given for mining Bitcoin blocks'),
(86, 14, '\n\n<h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\" > Intro </h2>\n<p>\n   Because  Airdrops have different tools depending on their class, this lesson provides practical steps for participating and benefiting from them.\n</p>\n<br><br>\n\n\n<section>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">Testnets</h2>\n<p class=\"pl-3\">\n    Testnets are networks used for testing purposes before launching on the mainnet. Airdrops on testnets reward users who interact with the platform during its development phase. This is a common way to engage early adopters and gather feedback before the official launch.\n    <br>\n    <br>\n</p>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"text-xl font-semibold pl-3 \">1. Testnet tools/process</h4>\n<p>\n    <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 list-inside space-y-2\">\n        <li>Visit the website and connect your burner wallet on the testnet\'s preferred network.</li>\n        <li>Get testnet tokens. The testnet guidelines should explain how to get testnet tokens.</li>\n        <li>Interact with the platform by performing actions like sending and receiving tokens across wallets, trading, providing liquidity, swapping between testnet tokens, bridging between networks, staking, or using specific features.</li>\n        </li>\n        <li>Complete any required tasks or forms to qualify for the airdrop.</li>\n        <li>Wait for the snapshot date to see if you qualify for the airdrop.</li>\n    </ol>\n    <br>\n</p>\n<p class=\"pl-3\">\n    <strong>NOTE:</strong> If you are using a mobile device, it is best to open the built-in browser of your wallet app, such as Trust Wallet or MetaMask, to access the testnet\'s website. This ensures that your wallet is properly connected and can smoothly interact with the testnet\'s features.\n</p>\n\n</section>\n\n<br><br>\n\n<section>\n    <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">Yapping</h2>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        Yapping is a term used to describe the process of engaging with a project on social media platforms to qualify for an airdrop. This typically involves following the project\'s official accounts, sharing posts, joining community groups, and completing other social tasks as specified by the project.\n        Yapping is often a requirement for users to prove their interest and support for the project, which can help increase the project\'s visibility and community engagement.\n        <br>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n    <h2 class=\"text-xl font-semibold pl-3\">Yapping tools/process</h2>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 list-inside space-y-2\">\n            <li>Create dedicated non-personal social media accounts on Twitter, Reddit, Medium, and Facebook.</li>\n            <li>Be active by posting your interests to maintain visibility, and grow your Twitter page to at least 500 followers, get verified if you can (verification is not necessary).</li>\n            <li>Go to the project\'s website, create an account, and connect your Twitter account.</li>\n            <li>Follow the project\'s official social media accounts (Twitter, Telegram, Discord, etc.).</li>\n            <li>Post or retweet specific posts as instructed by the project using the required tags and hashtags.</li>\n            <li> Get updates about the project by joining community groups and participating in discussions.</li>\n            <li>Complete any additional tasks such as filling out forms or creating content.</li>\n            <li>Invite and onboard new users using your referral links to increase your earnings.</li>\n            <li>Wait for the airdrop announcement to see if you qualify.</li>\n        </ol>\n    </p>\n\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        <strong>NOTE:</strong> Yapping is a common requirement for many airdrops, and it helps projects build a community of engaged users. However, it\'s important to be cautious and avoid spammy behavior by not excessively posting the same content, as this can lead to account suspensions or bans on social media platforms.\n        <br>\n        Always follow the project\'s guidelines and engage genuinely with the community.\n    </p>\n\n</section>\n<br>\n<br>\n\n\n<section>\n    <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">DEPINs</h2>\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        DEPINs, or Decentralized Physical Infrastructure Networks, are a class of airdrops that reward users for contributing to the development of decentralized physical infrastructure. This can include tasks like running nodes, providing resources, or participating in governance.\n        DEPINs aim to create a more resilient and decentralized network by incentivizing users to contribute to the physical infrastructure that supports blockchain networks.\n        <br>\n        <br>\n    </p>\n    <h2 class=\"text-xl font-semibold pl-3\">DEPINs tools/process</h2>\n    <p class=\"pl-5\">\n        <ol class=\"list-disc pl-5 list-inside space-y-2\">\n            <li>Identify a DEPIN project that interests you and has an active community.</li>\n            <li>Join the project\'s community channels (Discord, Telegram, etc.) to stay updated.</li>\n            <li>Run a node or provide resources as required by the project; This is done by downloading and installing certain applications or browser extensions on your device, and keeping it connected to the internet, so basically your device will keep running.</li>\n            <li>Participate in governance decisions if applicable.</li>\n            <li>Stick to the project\'s guidelines, do not try to game or cheat the system. </li>\n            <li>Complete any additional tasks as will be regularly announced to qualify.</li>\n            <li>Invite and onboard new users using your referral links to increase your earnings.</li>\n            <li>Wait for the snapshot date to see if you qualify for the airdrop.</li>\n        </ol>\n    </p>\n</section>\n<br>\n<br>\n\n<section>\n    <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">Important tips about Airdrops</h2>\n  <section class=\"pl-3\">\n    <p>\n      <strong>i. </strong>  Airdrops are not guaranteed, and the amount of tokens received can vary based on the project\'s criteria and your level of participation. Always do your own research (DYOR) before engaging in any airdrop activities, and be cautious of scams or phishing attempts.\n        <br>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n    <p> <strong>ii. </strong>\n        Airdrops require patience and consistent engagement with the project because some can go on for years. It\'s important to stay informed about the project\'s updates, participate in community discussions, and complete tasks as required to maximize your chances of receiving tokens.\n        <br>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n    <p> <strong>iii. </strong>\n        Airdrops can be a side job as they can be done from anywhere, at any time, and with little to no investment. However, it requires dedication and a willingness to learn about different projects and their ecosystems.\n        <br>    \n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n    <p> <strong>iv. </strong>\n        DEPINs can weaken your device if you are not careful, as they require your device to be constantly connected to the internet and running applications that may consume significant resources. It\'s important to monitor your device\'s performance and ensure it can handle the demands of running a node or providing resources; if it can\'t, then do not continue.\n        <br>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n    <p> <strong>v. </strong>\n        Always be cautious of scams and phishing attempts in the crypto space. Only participate in airdrops from reputable projects; airdrops asking you for any form of payment are a red flag and 90% of the time are not genuine.  Use official channels to verify the legitimacy of airdrop announcements, and never share your private keys or sensitive information with anyone.\n        <br>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n    <p> <strong>vi. </strong>\n        To claim your rewards, the project will make announcements on how to distribute rewards to participants; This may involve submitting a wallet address from an exchange or claiming on-chain to your connected wallet, which may require gas fees.\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n</section>\n</section>\n\n\n\n', 'Airdrops 2', NULL, 'What is the purpose of using a burner wallet on a testnet for an airdrop?', 'To interact with the platform without risking personal funds', 'To increase mining rewards on the mainnet', 'To swap tokens on centralized exchanges', 'To purchase NFTs from real users'),
(87, 14, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of the following is a requirement during Yapping airdrops?', 'Following project social media and engaging with content', 'Uploading identity documents to the blockchain', 'Mining tokens with high-end GPUs', 'Holding stablecoins in your exchange wallet'),
(88, 14, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is a major risk associated with DEPIN airdrops?', 'They may weaken your device due to constant internet and CPU usage', 'They can cause loss of liquidity on exchanges', 'They often lead to permanent wallet bans', 'They may force you to stake tokens immediately'),
(89, 14, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which activity is NOT typically required in a DEPIN airdrop?', 'Buying tokens through private sales', 'Running nodes or providing resources', 'Participating in governance', 'Using browser extensions or apps provided by the project'),
(90, 14, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What makes airdrops a viable side job for some people?', 'They require little to no investment and can be done from anywhere', 'They offer fixed monthly salaries paid in crypto', 'They involve contract-based employment on blockchains', 'They guarantee token value increases over time'),
(91, 14, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of the following is a red flag when evaluating an airdrop opportunity?', 'The project asks for payment to receive tokens', 'The project uses Telegram for community updates', 'The project rewards referrals', 'The project asks you to fill a claim form');
INSERT INTO `questions_and_answers` (`id`, `learning_cycle`, `material`, `material_title`, `lesson_video`, `question`, `answer`, `option_1`, `option_2`, `option_3`) VALUES
(92, 15, '  <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">Introduction to Crypto Trading</h2>\n      <p class=\"pl-3\"><strong>Crypto trading</strong> refers to the process of buying and selling cryptocurrencies with the aim of making a profit. Similar to stock trading, it involves speculating on the price movements of digital assets such as <strong>Bitcoin (BTC)</strong>, <strong>Ethereum (ETH)</strong>, <strong>Solana (SOL)</strong>, and many others.</p>\n      <p class=\"pl-3\"> The value of a crypto asset is determined by <strong>supply and demand</strong> in the open market, and is often influenced by technological developments, regulatory news, market sentiment, macroeconomic factors, and more; so profitable crypto trading is a special skill that is learned by concious effort and dedication to the crypto ecosystem.</p>\n    </section>\n    <br><br>\n\n    <section>\n      <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\" >Trading/Currency pairs</h2>\n\n    <p class=\"pl-3\"><strong>Trading pairs</strong> are combinations of two different currencies that can be traded for each other on an exchange. They represent the price relationship between two assets, typically one <strong>base currency</strong> and one <strong>quote currency</strong> ,  symbolized as <b>BASE/QUOTE</b>. For example, if you see the trading pair <strong>BTC/USDT</strong>, this means: you are buying or selling <strong>Bitcoin (BTC)</strong> using <strong>Tether (USDT)</strong>.</p>\n\n    <p class=\"pl-3\">\n      In (<b>ETH/BTC</b>) :\n      <ol  class=\"pl-3\">\n          <li><strong>ETH</strong> is the <strong>base currency</strong> i.e the one you want to buy or sell.</li>\n          <li><strong>BTC</strong> is the <strong>quote currency</strong> i.e  the one you use to pay or receive.</li>\n      </ol>\n      <span class=\"pl-3\">\n        If <b>ETH/BTC</b> = 0.07, it means that 1 <b>ETH</b> = <b>0.07 BTC</b>, so you need 0.07 <b>BTC</b> to buy 1 <b>ETH</b>, and if you sell 1 <b>ETH</b>, you will get 0.07 <b>BTC</b>.\n      </span>\n    </p>\n    <br>\n\n    <div>\n      <span>\n        Trading pairs matters because :\n      </span>\n\n      <ol class=\"pl-3 list-disc space-y-2 list-inside\">\n        <li><strong>They determine what you can trade</strong>\n            <p>Exchanges don’t let you trade any coin for any coin directly. You can only trade coins that have a <strong>direct pair</strong> listed.</p>\n        </li>\n        <li><strong>They affect your route</strong>\n            <p>Say you have USDT, and you want to buy a small token like <b> $XYZ </b>, but the exchange lists <b>$XYZ/BNB</b>, you will need to → buy <b>BNB</b> with <b>USDT</b> → then buy <b>$XYZ</b> with <b>BNB</b>.\n                <br>\n                This process is called a <strong>trading path</strong>.</p>\n        </li>\n        <li><strong>They define the price you see</strong>\n            <p>You will see coin prices based on the quote currency.</p>\n            <ul>\n                <li> <b> BTC/USDT</b> = $29,000; Means 1 <b>BTC</b> costs 29,000 <b>USDT</b>.</li>\n                <li><b>ETH/BTC</b> = $0.07; Means 1 <b>ETH</b> costs 0.07 <b>BTC</b>.</li>\n            </ul>\n        </li>\n    </ol>\n  </div>\n    <br>\n       \n    <p><strong>NOTE : </strong> Many stablecoins (like USDT or BUSD) are <strong>quote currencies</strong> because they offer a price tied to Fiat (dollar).</p>\n\n    <br>\n    <h2 class=\"text-xl font-semibold\">Types of trading pairs</h2>\n    <ol class=\"\'space-y-3 list-inside pl-3\">\n        <li><strong>Crypto-to-Stablecoin</strong> (e.g., BTC/USDT) <br>\n            <span class=\"pl-5\">Good for beginners and everyday crypto transactions, with an easy to understand value (in dollars).</li>\n\n        <li><strong>Crypto-to-Crypto</strong> (e.g., ETH/BTC)\n            <br> <span class=\"pl-5\"> Mainly used by experienced traders in exploring the DeFi ecosystem. </span></li>\n    </ol>\n    </section>\n\n    <br><br>\n\n    <section>\n      <h2 class=\"text-2xl\"> Types and strategies of Crypto trading</h2>\n      <p class=\"pl-3\">There are different styles and methods in crypto trading. Every trader can choose a style depending on their goals, time commitment, and risk appetite.</p>\n      <p>\n        Lets explore some of the most common types of crypto trading:\n      </p>\n\n      <h3 class=\"text-l font-semibold\">a. Spot trading</h3>\n      <p class=\"pl-3\">Spot trading is like buying candy at a store, you give your money and get the candy right away. In the same way, with spot trading, you use your money (like dollars or a digital coin) to buy a cryptocurrency, such as Bitcoin, at the price it costs right now. You get the crypto immediately and it’s yours. If its price goes up later, you can sell it and get more money. But if the price goes down, you might lose some money. So, spot trading means buying and selling crypto at the moment, just like shopping with real money.  It is the most common and straightforward type of trading.</p>\n      <br>\n      \n\n      <h3 class=\"text-l font-semibold\">b. Margin trading</h3>\n\n      <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        Margin trading is a type of trading that involves increasing your position using borrowed funds from the exchange, which allows you to trade with more money than you actually have. This can amplify your potential profits, but it also increases your risk of losses.\n\n        This trading will be discussed in more detail in the margin trading section of this lesson.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n\n\n\n      <h3 class=\"text-l font-semibold\">c. Futures trading</h3>\n      \n      <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        Futures trading are contracts that agree to buy/sell a cryptocurrency at a future date at a predetermined price. It is often used by traders to speculate on price movements or to hedge against potential losses in their existing positions. It is a more advanced trading strategy that requires a good understanding of the market and risk management.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n\n      <h3 class=\"txt-l font-semibold\">d. Derivatives and Options</h3>\n      <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        Derivatives and options are financial instruments that derive their value from an underlying asset, such as a cryptocurrency. They allow traders to speculate on the future price movements of the asset without actually owning it. This can be a complex and risky trading strategy that requires a good understanding of the market and risk management. \n      </p>\n      <br>\n      <h3 class=\"text-l font-semibold\">e. Arbitrage trading</h3>\n      <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        Arbitrage trading is a strategy that involves taking advantage of price differences between different exchanges or markets. Traders buy a cryptocurrency at a lower price on one exchange and sell it at a higher price on another exchange, making a profit from the price difference. This requires quick execution and can be risky if the prices change rapidly.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n      <h3 class=\"text-l font-semibold\">f. Algorithmic trading</h3>\n      <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        Algorithmic trading is a method of executing trades using computer algorithms and automated systems. It involves using predefined rules and strategies to analyze market data and execute trades at high speeds. This type of trading is often used by institutional investors and high-frequency traders to take advantage of market inefficiencies and execute large volumes of trades quickly. Due to the influx of AI and machine learning, algorithmic trading is becoming more accessible to retail traders as well.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n      <h3 class=\"text-l font-semibold\">g. Copy trading</h3>\n      <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        Copy trading is a strategy that allows traders to automatically copy the trades of experienced and successful traders. This can be done through social trading platforms or brokerage accounts that offer copy trading features. It is a way for less experienced traders to benefit from the expertise of others without having to make their own trading decisions.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n      <h3 class=\"text-l font-semibold\">h. Swing trading</h3>\n      <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        Swing trading is a strategy that involves holding positions for a few days to weeks to take advantage of short-term price movements. Traders analyze charts and market trends to identify potential entry and exit points, aiming to capture smaller price swings within a larger trend. This type of trading requires patience and a good understanding of technical analysis.\n      </p>\n      <br>\n  </section>\n<br>', 'Crypto trading', NULL, 'What does crypto trading involve?', 'Buying and selling cryptocurrencies to make profit', 'Creating new cryptocurrencies', 'Sending crypto from one wallet to another', 'Only mining digital coins'),
(93, 15, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'In the trading pair ETH/BTC, what does BTC represent?', 'The quote currency used to pay or receive', 'The base currency being bought or sold', 'A mining fee', 'An exchange token'),
(94, 15, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which trading strategy involves buying and selling crypto instantly like shopping?', 'Spot trading', 'Margin trading', 'Futures trading', 'Arbitrage trading'),
(95, 15, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is margin trading?', 'Using borrowed funds to increase your position size', 'Copying another trader’s strategy', 'Holding coins in cold storage', 'Only using stablecoins for trading'),
(96, 15, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which trading method profits from price differences on different exchanges?', 'Arbitrage trading', 'Copy trading', 'Swing trading', 'Spot trading'),
(97, 15, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which type of trading lets you automatically follow expert traders?', 'Copy trading', 'Futures trading', 'Spot trading', 'Algorithmic trading'),
(98, 16, '  <section>\n    \n        <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\"> Trading tools and platform</h2>\n        <p class=\"pl-3\">\n            Crypto trading tools includes all the applications that a trader uses to find tokens, perform analysis,  and finally execute a trade; These applications includes Exchanges, Dexscanning tools, market movement analyzers, Block explorers, AI systems and automated bots, e.t.c  \n            <br>\n            <br>\n            In this lesson we will discuss the popular tools and the fundamental ways to use them, however developing dependable skills of their usage takes time and concious effort.\n\n        </p>\n\n    </section>\n<br><br>\n\n<style>\n  table {\n    border-collapse: collapse;\n    width: 100%;\n  }\n\n  th, td {\n    border: 1px solid #ccc; /* adds both vertical and horizontal lines */\n    padding: 10px;\n    text-align: left;\n  }\n  th\n  {\n    text-align: center;\n  }\n    th:last-child, td:last-child {\n        border-right: none; /* remove right border on last column */\n    }\n     th:first-child, td:first-child {\n    border-left: none; /* remove left border on last column */\n  }\n</style>\n    <section>\n\n        <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\"> Exchanges   </h2>\n        <br>\n\n   <table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"10\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border: collapse\">\n  <thead>\n    <tr style=\"border-bottom: solid 1px pink;\">\n      <th>Exchange</th>\n      <th>Strengths</th>\n      <th>Weaknesses</th>\n      <th>Restrictions</th>\n      <th>Terms</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Binance</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Largest trading volume globally.<br>\n        Wide selection of cryptocurrencies.<br>\n        Low trading fees.<br>\n        Advanced trading features (futures, margin, etc.).\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Complex interface for beginners.<br>\n        Regulatory scrutiny in multiple countries.<br>\n        Limited fiat support in some regions.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Restricted in the US (Binance US is a separate entity).<br>\n        KYC is required for most services.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Tiered fee structure based on volume and BNB usage.<br>\n        Margin trading with up to 10x leverage.<br>\n        Supports staking and savings products.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Coinbase</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Extremely beginner-friendly.<br>\n        High liquidity.<br>\n        Regulated in the US.<br>\n        Strong security features.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        High fees compared to competitors,\n        Fewer listed assets than Binance\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Only available in select countries.<br>\n        Full KYC and ID verification is required.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        No margin trading on basic platform.<br>\n        Pro platform available for advanced traders.<br>\n        Transparent fee schedule.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Kraken</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Regulated and secure.<br>\n        Advanced trading tools.<br>\n        Supports margin and futures.<br>\n        Low fees for high-volume traders.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Interface can be intimidating for new users.<br>\n        Limited coin selection compared to Binance.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Some features restricted in certain US states.<br>\n        KYC is mandatory for most actions.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Offers staking and futures.<br>\n        Up to 5x leverage on margin.<br>\n        Transparent API support.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>KuCoin</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Broad selection of altcoins.<br>\n        Low trading fees.<br>\n        User-friendly interface.<br>\n        Passive income through lending and staking.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        No fiat-to-crypto trading (via third-party only).<br>\n        History of security breach (now improved).\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        No KYC required for low-volume users.<br>\n        There is limited access to fiat services in some regions.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Offers spot, margin, and futures trading.<br>\n        Lending features available.<br>\n        Rewards for KCS token holders.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>OKX</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Advanced trading features.<br>\n        Deep liquidity.<br>\n        Supports DeFi, Web3, and DEX connections .\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Can be complex for beginners.<br>\n        Limited fiat gateways.<br>\n        Less well-known in the US.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Restricted or limited in the US.<br>\n        KYC is required for higher withdrawals and leverage.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Offers perpetual futures, options, and staking.<br>\n        Up to 125x leverage on derivatives.<br>\n        Built-in Web3 wallet features.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Gate.io</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Huge variety of tokens.<br>\n        Low fees.<br>\n        User-friendly interface.<br>\n        Strong security measures. <br>\n        Margin & futures support.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Less known in the US.<br>\n        Some features can be overwhelming for beginners.<br>\n        Regulatory issues in some regions.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        KYC is required for most features.<br>\n        Restricted in some regions.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Offers copy trading, dual investments.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>Bybit</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Fast-growing exchange.<br>\n        Strong futures platform.<br>\n        Clean UI.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Less variety of altcoins compared to Binance.<br>\n        Limited fiat onramps.<br>\n        Not available in some regions.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        US users restricted.<br>\n        KYC is required for high withdrawals.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Up to 100x leverage.<br>\n        Copy trading, launchpad, bots.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td><strong>MEXC</strong></td>\n      <td>\n        Fast listings of new tokens.<br>\n        No KYC for small withdrawals.<br>\n        Wide asset support.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Less known in the US.<br>\n        Limited fiat options.<br>\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Some regions are restricted.<br>\n        Limited fiat options.\n      </td>\n      <td>\n        Margin & futures trading.<br>\n        Launchpad, staking, earn features.\n      </td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n\n\n    </section>\n    <br><br>\n\n    <section>\n      <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">Why the restrictions?</h2>\n      <br>\n      <p>\n        There are several reasons why some exchanges have restrictions on their services, especially in certain countries or regions. These restrictions can include limitations on trading, deposits, withdrawals, or even access to the platform altogether. Here are some common reasons for these restrictions:\n      </p>\n      <ol class=\"pl-3 list-disc space-y-2 list-inside\">\n        <li><strong>Regulatory Compliance:</strong> Exchanges must comply with local laws and regulations, which can vary significantly between countries. Some jurisdictions have strict rules regarding cryptocurrency trading, requiring exchanges to obtain licenses or adhere to specific operational standards.</li>\n        <li><strong>Security Concerns:</strong> To protect users from potential fraud or hacking, exchanges may restrict access from regions known for high levels of cybercrime or where they cannot guarantee adequate security measures.</li>\n        <li><strong>Legal Issues:</strong> Some countries have outright bans on cryptocurrency trading or specific types of transactions, leading exchanges to restrict access to those regions.</li>\n        <li><strong>Risk Management:</strong> Exchanges may limit services in certain areas to manage risks associated with market volatility, liquidity issues, or potential money laundering activities.</li>\n        <li><strong>Operational Challenges:</strong> Technical limitations or challenges in providing reliable services in certain regions can also lead to restrictions.</li>\n        <li><strong>Tax Compliance:</strong> Some exchanges may restrict services in countries where they cannot effectively manage tax reporting requirements for users.</li>\n      </ol>\n      <br>\n      <p>\n        It is important for users to be aware of these restrictions and to check the terms and conditions of the exchange they are using. If you are in a restricted region, you may need to use a different exchange that operates legally in your area or consider using decentralized exchanges (DEXs) that do not have such restrictions.\n      </p>\n    </section>\n    <br>\n\n    <section>\n      <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">DEX scanning tools</h2>\n      <p class=\"pl-3\">\n          DEX scanning tools are essential for traders who want to analyze decentralized exchanges (DEXs) and make informed decisions. They provide real-time data on token prices, trading volumes, liquidity, and other important metrics. They help users identify potential trading opportunities, track market trends, and avoid scams or low-quality tokens.\n          <br>\n          Here are some popular DEX scanning tools and their features:\n        </p>\n        <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        <ol class=\"list-none list-inside pl-3 space-y-2\">\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://www.dextools.io\" target=\"_blank\">DEXTools</a>:</strong> Offers live charts, liquidity tracking, and scam detection across DEXs like Uniswap and PancakeSwap.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://dexscreener.com\" target=\"_blank\">DexScreener</a>:</strong> Tracks live prices, volumes, and trades across chains, great for spotting early market trends.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://tokensniffer.com\" target=\"_blank\">TokenSniffer</a>:</strong> Analyzes smart contracts to detect scams and honeypots. Useful for evaluating unknown tokens.\n          </li>\n        </ol>\n        </p>\n        <br><br>\n\n        <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">Market Movement Analyzers</h2>\n        <p>\n          Market movement analyzers are tools that help traders track and analyze the price movements of cryptocurrencies. They provide insights into market trends, trading volumes, and price patterns, enabling users to make informed trading decisions.\n          <br>\n          Here are some popular market movement analyzers:\n        </p>\n        <p class=\"pl-3 \">\n        <ol class=\"list-none list-inside pl-3 space-y-2\">\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://coinmarketcap.com\" target=\"_blank\">CoinMarketCap</a>:</strong> Tracks price, volume, market cap, and trends. Useful for gauging overall market sentiment.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://cryptoquant.com\" target=\"_blank\">CryptoQuant</a>:</strong> Provides insights using exchange flows, whale tracking, and miner activity for market predictions.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://santiment.net\" target=\"_blank\">Santiment</a>:</strong> Combines social media, developer, and on-chain data to offer predictive signals.\n          </li>\n        </ol>\n      </p>\n      <br><br>\n\n        <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold\">Block explorers</h2>\n        <p class=\"pl-3\">\n          Block explorers are essential tools for anyone involved in cryptocurrency trading or blockchain technology. They allow users to view and analyze transactions, blocks, and addresses on a blockchain network. These tools provide transparency and help users verify transactions, track wallet balances, and monitor network activity.\n          <br>\n          Here are some popular block explorers for different blockchain networks:\n        </p>\n        \n        <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        <ol class=\"list-none list-inside pl-3 space-y-2\">\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://etherscan.io\" target=\"_blank\">Etherscan (Ethereum)</a>:</strong> Explore Ethereum transactions, wallet balances, and smart contract activities.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://bscscan.com\" target=\"_blank\">BscScan (Binance Smart Chain)</a>:</strong> Offers similar functionality for BSC, including DeFi interaction tracking.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://solscan.io\" target=\"_blank\">Solscan (Solana)</a>:</strong> Used for exploring Solana blockchain activities including transactions and validator data.\n          </li>\n        </ol>\n        </p>\n        <br><br>\n\n        <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold \">AI systems</h2>\n        <p class=\"pl-3\">\n          AI systems are increasingly being integrated into crypto trading to provide advanced analytics, predictive modeling, and automated trading strategies. These systems can analyze vast amounts of data, identify patterns, and make real-time decisions to optimize trading outcomes.\n          <br>\n          Here are some popular AI systems used in crypto trading:\n        </p>\n        <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        <ol class=\"list-none list-inside pl-3 space-y-2\">\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://app.intotheblock.com\" target=\"_blank\">IntoTheBlock</a>:</strong> AI-based insights like whale concentration, holder behavior, and market intelligence.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://www.kaiko.com\" target=\"_blank\">Kaiko AI</a>:</strong> Institutional-grade AI analytics focusing on liquidity, market data, and trade analysis.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://openai.com/chatgpt\" target=\"_blank\">ChatGPT (Custom)</a>:</strong> When integrated with data feeds, can assist with predictions, strategy creation, and sentiment analysis.\n          </li>\n        </ol>\n        </p>\n        <br><br>\n\n        <h2 class=\"text-2xl font-bold \">Automated bots</h2>\n        <p class=\"pl-3\">\n          Automated trading bots are software programs that execute trades on behalf of users based on predefined strategies or algorithms. They can help traders take advantage of market opportunities 24/7 without the need for constant monitoring. Here are some popular automated trading bots:\n        </p>\n        <p class=\"pl-3\">\n        <ol class=\"list-none list-inside pl-3 space-y-2\">\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://3commas.io\" target=\"_blank\">3Commas</a>:</strong> Multi-strategy bot platform supporting DCA, grid, and copy trading on major exchanges.\n          </li> \n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://www.pionex.com\" target=\"_blank\">Pionex</a>:</strong> Comes with built-in grid and arbitrage bots. Beginner-friendly and reliable for passive income.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong><a href=\"https://hummingbot.org\" target=\"_blank\">Hummingbot</a>:</strong> Open-source, code-driven bot suitable for advanced users focused on liquidity mining and custom strategies.\n          </li>\n        </ol>\n        </p>\n    </section>\n    <br><br>\n   <div class=\"quickbox\">\n     <h2 class=\"qbheading\"><b class=\"ideabulb\">&#128161; </b> <b class=\"qbheading\"> PLATFORM UTILITY TIP </b> </h2>\n    <br>\n    <p>\n      As a newbie, majority of this tools will not make sense to you yet, but as you progress in your crypto journey, you will find them useful. It is important to take your time to learn and understand how each tool works, and how they can be used to enhance your trading experience.\n      <br>\n       This list though not exhaustive, answers the question of \"what to buy, when to buy,why to buy, and how to buy\" in the crypto ecosystem. There are more tools and alternatives than the ones listed here, and you will discover them as you continue to explore the crypto space. They are essential for making informed trading decisions and maximizing your potential profits. \n       <br>\n       This lesson is just an introduction to the tools, you will learn more about them by experimenting and experience, or specific lessons about them.\n    </p>\n   </div>\n   <br><br>', 'Trading platforms and tools', NULL, 'Which exchange is known for having the largest trading volume globally and advanced features like futures and margin trading?', 'Binance', 'Coinbase', 'Kraken', 'KuCoin'),
(99, 16, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which tool is primarily used to scan decentralized exchanges and detect scam tokens or honeypots?', 'TokenSniffer', 'CoinMarketCap', 'CryptoQuant', 'Etherscan'),
(100, 16, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'What is a common reason for regional restrictions on crypto exchanges?', 'Regulatory compliance', 'Lack of user interest', 'High trading fees', 'Token volatility'),
(101, 16, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which platform provides AI-based insights such as whale concentration and holder behavior?', 'IntoTheBlock', 'Hummingbot', 'Pionex', '3Commas'),
(102, 16, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which of the following is a feature of the Kraken exchange?', 'Supports margin and futures trading', 'No KYC required for most actions', 'Offers copy trading and dual investments', 'Launchpad and staking only'),
(103, 16, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Which automated bot is open-source and suited for liquidity mining and custom strategies?', 'Hummingbot', 'Kaiko AI', 'DexTools', 'Pionex');
